title: b'CIW-IUS 2022'
description: b' First Combined International Workshop on Interactive Urgent Supercomputing'
Call For Papers: b"\n========================================================================\r                            CALL FOR PAPERS\r                  First Combined International Workshop\r                  on Interactive Urgent Supercomputing\r                        In conjunction with SC22\r           Monday, November 14, 2022, 8:30am - 12:00pm CST\r        Kay Bailey Hutchison Convention Center, Dallas, TX, USA\r                   Website: https://www.urgenthpc.com\r                       Twitter: @interactivehpc\r========================================================================\r Submission deadline: 15th August 2022 (AoE)\rAuthor notification: 9th September 2022\rCamera Ready: 30th September 2022 (AoE)\rWorkshop: Monday morning, 14th November 2022\r [NOTE: SC22 is currently planning for this year's workshops to be held in\rperson. This will be updated as the COVID-19 situation progresses.]\r Authors are invited to submit unpublished, original work, related to the\rinteractive and/or urgent use of high-performance computing (HPC) in two\rcategories, to be evaluated separately:\r * Full research paper: Describing novel research, up to 10 pages.\r* Hot topic paper: Less mature/late breaking results, up to 6 pages.\r Accepted authors will be invited to speak at the workshop and to submit their\rpapers for publication in SC22 workshop proceedings. All submitted papers\rwill be peer-reviewed and accepted papers will be published by the IEEE\rComputer Society.\r Scope\r=====\rThis workshop will bring together stakeholders, researchers, and practitioners\rfrom across the HPC community who are working, or interested, in the fields of\rinteractive HPC and the use of supercomputing for urgent decision-making.\rSuccess stories, case studies, and best practices will be shared across the\rtwo themes with a view to enhancing the communities' activities and\ridentifying new opportunities for collaboration.  The challenges associated\rwith interactive and urgent HPC are difficult ones, and productively\rsupporting these capabilities requires a number of advances across a range of\rtechnical, policy, and even sociological realms. While there are multiple\refforts to use HPC for disaster response, and progress has been made on\rinteractivity in HPC, the effort is largelly disjointed, piecemeal, and done\ron an institute-by-institute basis. With so much replication of effort, there\ris significant value to be unlocked if the SC community can come together to\raddress technical, policy, and sociological issues relevant to interactive and\rurgent HPC.\r Call for Papers\r===============\rWe invite you to submit both full and hot-topic research papers detailing\roriginal work in the interactive use of HPC and/or the use of HPC for urgent\rdecision-making. Topics of interest for workshop submissions include, but are\rnot limited to:\r * Example use-cases and case-studies that use HPC for interactivity and/or urgent decision making\r* Techniques for integrating HPC workflows with data driven approaches\r* Approaches to verify and validate unreliable real-time data, for instance from sensors, IoT, and satellites\r* System design for data reduction and pre-processing at source, for instance using edge computing and heterogeneous resources such as FPGAs\r* Implementation experiences and lessons learned by staff at HPC centers\r* Algorithmic techniques to guarantee result generation in specific time frames, such as result refinement which generates more accurate results as time progresses\r* Studies of leveraging HPC for workloads with real-time time constraints\r* Changes to existing HPC technologies and policies that are required to support using HPC interactively\r* The ability for HPC codes to adapt their resource requirements dynamically, for instance via elastic compute\r* Visualisation and presentation techniques to support rapid and accurate urgent decision making by the end user\r* Reduction and feature extraction of results to highlight critical issues of interest\r* Complimenting results with provenance data for additional context and certainty\r* Maintaining security while providing interactivity in supercomputing\r* Strategies for leveraging interactivity for reproducible science\r* Impact of increased interactivity on how HPC centers operate\r Paper Submission Guidelines\r===========================\rPlease submit full research papers (up to 10 pages) or hot-topic papers (up to\r6 pages) via Linklings: https://bit.ly/3nfAvfd\r Further Information\r===================\rVisit our website at https://www.urgenthpc.com for more detailed information\rabout this worksop, and feel free to contact the organizing committee directly\rusing contact details listed there.\r\n"

Call For Papers: b"\n[ Apologies if you got multiple copies of this email]\r----------------------------------------------------------------\r            Call for Papers\r         IEEE Intelligent Informatics Bulletin \r          URL: http://ieee-iib.org \r----------------------------------------------------------------\r AIMS: The IEEE Intelligent Informatics Bulletin (IEEE IIB) is the official publication of the Technical Committee on Intelligent Informatics (TCII) of the IEEE Computer Society. It aims at promoting the excellent research on the wide spectrum of intelligent informatics, as well as displaying the news/reports on TCII related conferences and other activities. The Technical Committee on Intelligent Informatics (TCII) of the IEEE Computer Society deals with tools and systems using cognitive and intelligent paradigms such as machine learning incl. deep learning, natural language processing, medical informatics, knowledge engineering incl. knowledge graphs, data mining, Web intelligence, brain informatics, intelligent agent technology, parallel and distributed information processing  with research and applications in big data, computer vision, virtual reality, recommender systems, social media, Internet of Things, smart city, intelligent transportation systems, robotics, humaniods, self-driving cars, wearable devices, and so on. \r Areas and topics include, but not limited to: \r* Machine Learning \r* Knowledge Engineering and Knowledge Management\r* Data Mining\r* Information Retrieval\r* Data Science and Big Data\r* Web Intelligence\r* Intelligent Agent Technology\r* Medical Informatics \r* Computer vision\r* virtual reality\r* Internet of Things\r* Recommender Systems\r* Parallel and Distributed Information\r The submissions to the IEEE Intelligent Informatics Bulletin can be, but not limited to, the following types:\r* Research Articles\r* Feature Articles and/or Special Issues\r* R & D Profiles (R & D centers and organizations; interview profiles on individual `stars'; projects; products)\r* Book Reviews\r Manuscripts accepted by IEEE IIB will be published and distributed once to twice a year in both hardcopies (ISSN 1727-5997) and electronic copies (ISSN 1727-6004) to all the members of the IEEE TCII. \r ----------------------------------------------------------------\rSubmission Instructions\r----------------------------------------------------------------\r Submissions should be prepared and submitted through the following hyperlink:\r http://ieee-iib.org/submission.html \r A coverletter should be included with a statement of the type of submission. \r Enquires should be directed to: editor@ieee-iib.org\r  \n"

title: b'SoCom4Good 2022'
description: b'Research Topic (a.k.a. Special Issue) \xe2\x80\x9cSocial Computing for Good\xe2\x80\x9d, Frontiers in Big Data'
Categories: b'social computing' b'social good' b'social media mining' b'machine learning'
Call For Papers: b"\nEvery day, online communities create massive amounts of data worldwide. One popular use of social networks is to provide a timely and cost-effective option for reflecting real-world occurrences. Users of social networks can transmit information in a dynamic, seamless way practically anywhere and anytime. Social computing, a branch of computer science concerned with the intersection of social behavior and computational systems, arose as a result of the advent of social network technologies and platforms. Social computing applications are fundamentally linked to those that harness social network users' behaviors, ideas, and emotions, such as stock price prediction, promoting items or advertisements, extracting users' opinions to enhance product development processes, analyzing political information, and so on.\r Social good can be described as anything that helps the most people in the most significant way imaginable. While applications of knowledge extracted from social networks are vast, only a small set are devoted to doing good for society. For example, real-time analysis of Twitter data has been used to model earthquake warning detection systems, identify medical and emergency needs during recovery from natural disasters (such as the Haiti Earthquake), detect the spread of influenza-like illness, and discover abusive behaviors in social networks. Furthermore, many studies have investigated the use of social media to monitor real-world population-wide and individual health, such as drinking problems, epidemics, drug abuse, and mental illness. With the recent outbreak of COVID-19, many studies showed that social media could be used to monitor depression and public discourses during the pandemic. This research topic invites manuscripts that address intelligent applications and computational techniques related to utilizing social networks or social media data for social good. Survey and review papers addressing the relevant issues are also welcome.\r Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\r- Intelligent applications of social computing in public health, sustainability, environment, equality, justice, education, cultural heritage, peace, economics, public welfare, etc\r- Mining social media data for policy development, smart government, and Sustainable Development Goals (SDG)\r- Investigating fraud, collusion, corruption, and criminal activities using social networks\r- Innovative and intelligent computational technologies, such as artificial intelligence, natural language processing (NLP), deep learning, computer vision, graph mining techniques, etc., that facilitate utilizing social media data for social good\r- Resource construction from social media data that enables social good applications\r This research topic strongly emphasizes both the computational and real-world impact aspects of social computing for social good applications. Submitted manuscripts should clearly define research questions and novel contributions as well as present rigorous empirical studies and evaluations of the proposed methodologies. Furthermore, societal implications and relevant ethical issues should also be discussed. Ethical issues may involve privacy concerns regarding data collection, storage, and processing of social media data and reproducibility of the research.\rEvery submission through the Data Analytics and Social Impact section must have a clear, strong, and demonstrated social impact and discussions of ethical choices and values as well a discussion of the human impact of the work.\r  Keywords: Social Computing, Social Good, Social Network Analytics, Social Media Mining, Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning\n\t"

title: b'WNUT@COLING 2022'

Call For Papers: b'\nThe 8th Workshop on Noisy User-generated Text (WNUT@COLING 2022)\r  The WNUT Workshop will be collocated with COLING 2022 (Hybrid - Gyeongju, Republic of Korea). The website for the workshop is at:  \r http://noisy-text.github.io/\r The WNUT workshop focuses on Natural Language Processing applied to noisy user-generated text, such as that found in social media, online reviews, crowdsourced data, web forums, clinical records, and language learner essays. \r We seek submissions of long and short papers on original and unpublished work (same format and page limit as COLING main conference). All accepted submissions will be presented as posters. Additionally, selected submissions will be presented orally. We have Best Paper Awards sponsored by Megagon Labs this year.\r Topics of interest include but are not limited to:\r * NLP Preprocessing of Noisy Text\r  - Part of speech tagging\r  - Named entity tagging, including a wide range of categories, e.g. product names\r  - Chunking of user-generated text\r  - Parsing\r* Text Normalization and Error Correction\r  - Normalizing noisy text for downstream tasks and for human readability\r  - Error detection and correction\r* Robustness to Noise, both Natural and Adversarial\r* Multilingual NLP in noisy text\r* Machine Translation of Noisy Text\r* Sentiment analysis\r* Crowdsourcing of text data\r* User prediction, e.g. gender, age, etc\r* Stylistics, e.g. formality, politeness, etc\r* Colloquial language, e.g. code-switching, idiom detection\r* Bilingual translation of the noisy text\r* Paraphrase identification and semantic similarity of short text or noisy text\r* Information extraction from noisy text\r* Domain adaptation to user-generated text\r* Geolocation prediction\r* Global and regional trend detection and event extraction\r* Detecting rumors, contradictory information, sarcasm, and humor on social media\r* Extracting user demographics, profiles, and major life events\r* Temporal aspects of user-generated content (resolving time expressions, concept drift, diachronic analyses, etc...)\r  = IMPORTANT DATES =\r * August 19, 2022: Submission Deadline (dual-submission w/ COLING main conference allowed)\r* September 7, 2022: Acceptance Notification\r* September 14, 2022: Camera-ready Deadline\r* October 17, 2022: Workshop Day\r  = ORGANIZERS =\r Tim Baldwin (University of Melbourne)\rAfshin Rahimi (University of Queensland)\rWei Xu (Georgia Institute of Technology)\rAlan Ritter (Georgia Institute of Technology)\r  = SUBMISSION =\r Formatting should be according to COLING 2022 specifications.\rDual submission is allowed but must state at the time of submission.\r Please submit through the START system at the following URL:\rhttps://www.softconf.com/coling2022/W-NUT_2022\r   \n'

Call For Papers: b'\nIEEE Transactions on Emerging Topics in Computing (TETC) seeks submissions for the upcoming special section on Approximate Data Processing: Computing, Storage, and Applications.\r This special section is devoted to covering: 1) recent advances in hardware, algorithms, and implementations for error-resilient (approximate) systems and 2) techniques for approximation focusing on storage/memory, data computation, and advanced designs of data processing systems. Relevant topics of interest to this special section include (but are not limited to):\r - Fundamental principles and techniques for approximate computing\r- Approximate schemes for data storage and related schemes, such as in-memory computing\r- Schemes for approximation in compiler, programming language, and software layer design\r- Approximate arithmetic computation using new number formats\r- Evaluation methods and error analysis of approximate systems\r- Logic synthesis/ EDA tools for approximate computing/storage designs\r- Hardware reliability/security for approximate computing/storage systems\r- Approximate schemes for emerging computing paradigms (such as stochastic, machine learning, probabilistic, and big data)\r- Novel applications of approximate data processing\r Important Dates\r- Submissions Due: 15 October 2022\r- Initial Notification (Accept/Reject/Revise, Tentative): 15 January 2023\r- Revisions Due: 15 March 2023\r- Final Notifications (Tentative): 1 May 2023\r- Publication (Tentative): After July 2023\r If you have any questions, please contact the guest editors at tetcsiadp@gmail.com.\r\n'

Call For Papers: b"\nICMCE 2023 [Ei Compendex & Scopus]\r Full Name: 2023 11th International Conference on Mechatronics and Control Engineering (ICMCE 2023)\rShort Name: ICMCE 2023\rTime: January 29-31, 2023\rPlace: Athens, Greece \rWebsite: http://www.icmce.org/    \r ICMCE 2023 marks the 11th Anniversary of the ICMCE conferences. ICMCE is a premier, annual forum for researchers and scholars from multiple disciplines to come together to share knowledge, discuss ideas, exchange information, and learn about cutting-edge research in diverse fields with the common theme of mechatronics and control engineering. We look forward your contributions to ICMCE 2023!\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Call for Paper\rTopics of interest for submission include, but are not limited to:\r1.Mechatronics:\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Acoustics and Noise Control\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Biomedical Engineering\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Computational Fluid Dynamics\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Dynamics and Vibration\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Emerging Renewable Energy\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Fuels and Combustion\r\xe2\x80\xa2 GeoMechatronics\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Heat and Mass Transfer\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Instrumentation and Control\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Internal Combustion Engines\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Machinery and Machine Design\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Nonlinear Dynamics\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Oil and Gas Exploration\r...\r2.Control Engineering:\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Modeling of Complex Systems\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Linear Systems\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Nonlinear Systems and Control\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Fuzzy and Neural Systems\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Estimation and Identification\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Fault Detection\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Process Control & Instrumentation\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Integrated Manufacturing\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Factory Modeling and Automation\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Petri-Nets and Applications\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Micro and Nano Systems\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Sensor Networks, Networked Control\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Optimal Control\r...\rFor details about topics, please visit at http://www.icmce.org/cfp.html.\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Conference Proceedings\rSubmitted papers will go through a rigorous full peer review process. The accepted papers (registered and presented) of ICMCE 2023 will be included into ICMCE 2023 Conference Proceedings, which will be indexed by Ei Compendex and Scopus.\r  \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Submission Methods\r1. Call For Papers: b'\nICMIT 2023--Ei Compendex and Scopus\r \xe2\x98\x85Full Name: 2023 9th International Conference on Manufacturing and Industrial Technologies (ICMIT 2023)\r\xe2\x98\x85Abbreviation: ICMIT 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Web: http://www.icmit.org/\r\xe2\x98\x85Time: January 29-31, 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Venue: Athens, Greece\r It is our pleasure to welcome all participants to 2023 9th International Conference on Manufacturing and Industrial Technologies (ICMIT 2023), which will be held during January 29-31, 2023 at Athens, Greece. ICMIT 2023 is the 9th year of the conference, since its inception in 2014. The purpose of ICMIT 2023 is to promote activities in various areas of Manufacturing and Industrial Technology by providing a forum for exchange of ideas, presentation of technical achievements and discussion of future directions. The ICMIT brings together an international community of experts to discuss the state-of-the-art, new research results, perspectives of future developments, and innovative applications relevant to intelligent and computer control systems, robotics, 3D printing, factory communications and automation, flexible manufacturing, data acquisition and signal processing, vision systems, and power electronics, and other related areas.\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Call for Papers\rTopics of interest for submission include, but are not limited to: including the following:\t\r**MANUFACTURING SYSTEM AND TECHNOLOGIES\rManufacturing Process Simulation\rCIMS and Manufacturing System\rVibration Measuring and Reliability Analysis\rFinite Element Analysis and structure optimization\r...\r**MATERIAL SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY IN MANUFACTURING\rArtificial Material\rForming\rNovel Material Fabrication\rGreen Manufacturing\r...\rMore Topics, please visit at http://www.icmit.org/cfp.html\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Paper Publication\rAfter a careful reviewing process, all the accepted papers of ICMIT 2023 will be published into Conference Proceedings, which will be submitted for indexing to by Ei Compendex and Scopus.\r  \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Paper Submission\r\xe2\x98\x85A. Call For Papers: b'\nICMIT 2023--Ei Compendex and Scopus\r \xe2\x98\x85Full Name: 2023 9th International Conference on Manufacturing and Industrial Technologies (ICMIT 2023)\r\xe2\x98\x85Abbreviation: ICMIT 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Web: http://www.icmit.org/\r\xe2\x98\x85Time: January 29-31, 2023\r\xe2\x98\x85Venue: Athens, Greece\r It is our pleasure to welcome all participants to 2023 9th International Conference on Manufacturing and Industrial Technologies (ICMIT 2023), which will be held during January 29-31, 2023 at Athens, Greece. ICMIT 2023 is the 9th year of the conference, since its inception in 2014. The purpose of ICMIT 2023 is to promote activities in various areas of Manufacturing and Industrial Technology by providing a forum for exchange of ideas, presentation of technical achievements and discussion of future directions. The ICMIT brings together an international community of experts to discuss the state-of-the-art, new research results, perspectives of future developments, and innovative applications relevant to intelligent and computer control systems, robotics, 3D printing, factory communications and automation, flexible manufacturing, data acquisition and signal processing, vision systems, and power electronics, and other related areas.\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Call for Papers\rTopics of interest for submission include, but are not limited to: including the following:\t\r**MANUFACTURING SYSTEM AND TECHNOLOGIES\rManufacturing Process Simulation\rCIMS and Manufacturing System\rVibration Measuring and Reliability Analysis\rFinite Element Analysis and structure optimization\r...\r**MATERIAL SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY IN MANUFACTURING\rArtificial Material\rForming\rNovel Material Fabrication\rGreen Manufacturing\r...\rMore Topics, please visit at http://www.icmit.org/cfp.html\r \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Paper Publication\rAfter a careful reviewing process, all the accepted papers of ICMIT 2023 will be published into Conference Proceedings, which will be submitted for indexing to by Ei Compendex and Scopus.\r  \xe2\x98\x85\xe2\x98\x85Paper Submission\r\xe2\x98\x85A. title: b'IGI-GBC 2022'
description: b'Call for Book Chapters - IGI- Global-Dynamics of Swarm Intelligence Health Analysis for the Next Generation'
Call For Papers: b"\nCall for Quality Book Chapters \r Dynamic of Swarm Intelligence Health Analysis for Next Generation.\r To be Published by IGI- Global Publications ( Scopus and Web of Science Indexed)\r  Descriptions:\r The book discusses the role of people's behavioral activity in the evolution of the traditional medical system to an intelligent system. This book is based on the development of technical improvements considered in the process of intelligent systems by using cognitive techniques, swarm intelligence deep learning, and machine learning techniques. These techniques are used for multimodal biomedical data processing and non-invasive interpretation which efficiently improves the patient interpretation quality. Moreover, it highlights the challenges of developing and proposing new ideas regarding the out-of-hospital dedicated systems directions.\r Specific topics of interest of this book include but are not limited to the following\r 1.Swarm Intelligence analysis in medical settings: Introduction, Applications, New opportunities and challenges.\r2.Adverse effects and impact in society:  Prediction and avoidance of adverse effects with the help of Swarm Intelligence\r3.An Evaluation of Swarm Intelligence analytic Tools, techniques approaches in Medical Health care Analysis.\r4.Patients Assisted system based on social media content adopting Swarm Intelligence analysis health care system.\r5.Machine Learning techniques for Swarm Intelligence analysis to predict outbreaks, Epidemic and Pandemic in Healthcare. \r6.Medical Text Analytics and its Applications: Methodologies integrated with Swarm Intelligence analysis.\r7.Artificial Intelligence tools and techniques Incorporated with Swarm Intelligence analysis on health care Application.\r8.Inter-professional Health care Collaboration: A qualitative and Effective Exploration of Facilitators, Barriers to Collaboration.\r9.A Modern Approach of Swarm Intelligence Analysis in Big Data: Methods, Tools, Applications, and Open Challenges.\r10.E- Health forum: Swarm Intelligence Analysis features construction procedure in medical care application.\r11.IoT Data in Swarm Intelligence Analysis: impacts on Decision oriented Application of IoT framework in Health care area.\r12.Various Learning Approaches for Swarm Intelligence Health care Analysis in Cloud Computing.\r13.Swarm Intelligence Analysis of Health care prediction techniques based on Social Media data.\r14.Development and design Methodologies applied in smart Application of Swarm Intelligence Health care Analysis.\r15.Ethical implications of Swarm Intelligence health care analysis to the individual and the society. \r Submission Guidelines\rAuthors are invited to submit their chapters electronically to this link\r https://www.igi-global.com/publish/call-for-papers/call-details/5997\r Authors should submit their original work that must not be submitted or currently under consideration for publication anywhere.\r Important Dates:\rAbstract Submission : July 13 2022\rFull chapter submission: September 25, 2022\rFirst Decision: November 08, 2022\rRevision: December 20, 2022\rFinal Chapter submission: January 03, 2023\r Any questions about this book, please feel free to contact\rDr. A. Suresh Kumar, Professor\rDepartment of Computer Science and Engineering\rGraphic Era Deemed to be University, UK, India\rsureshkumar.cse@geu.ac.in\r  \n"

12thInternational Conference on Software Engineering and Applications (SEA 2023)\r

March 18 ~ 19, 2023, Vienna, Austria

Due to the current COVID-19 pandemic, registered authors are now able to present their work through our online platforms.

Scope & Topics

12thInternational Conference on Software Engineering and Applications (SEA 2023) will provide an excellent international forum for sharing knowledge and results in theory, methodology and applications of Software Engineering and Applications. The goal of this conference is to bring together researchers and practitioners from academia and industry to focus on understanding Modern software engineering concepts and establishing new collaborations in these areas.\r

Authors are solicited to contribute to the conference by submitting articles that illustrate research results, projects, surveying works and industrial experiences that describe significant advances in the areas of Software Engineering and Applications\r

Topics of interest include, but are not limited to, the following

  • The Software Process\r
  • Software Engineering Practice\r
  • Web Engineering\r
  • Quality Management\r
  • Managing Software Projects\r
  • Advanced Topics in Software Engineering\r
  • Multimedia and Visual Software Engineering\r
  • Software Maintenance and Testing\r
  • Languages and Formal Methods\r
  • Web-based Education Systems and Learning Applications\r
  • Software Engineering Decision Making\r
  • Knowledge-based Systems and Formal Methods\r
  • Search Engines and Information Retrieval\r
  • Devops Model, Practices, Challenges

Paper Submission

Authors are invited to submit papers through the conference Submission System by October 20, 2022 . Submissions must be original and should not have been published previously or be under consideration for publication while being evaluated for this conference. The proceedings of the conference will be published by Computer Science Conference Proceedings in Computer Science & Information Technology (CS & IT) series (Confirmed).

Selected papers from SEA 2023, after further revisions, will be published in the special issue of the following journals.

  • International Journal of Software Engineering & Applications (IJSEA)- ERA Indexed
  • International Journal of Web & Semantic Technology (IJWesT)
  • International Journal of Security, Privacy and Trust Management ( IJSPTM )
  • Computer Science & Engineering: An International Journal (CSEIJ)
  • Advanced Computing: An International Journal (ACIJ)
  • Information Technology in Industry (ITII)

Important Dates

Submission Deadline: October 20, 2022
Authors Notification: December 20, 2022
Final Manuscript Due: December 28, 2022

title: b'VRST 2022'
description: b'Virtual Reality Software and Technology'
Categories: b'virtual reality' b'augmented reality' b'computer graphics'
Call For Papers: b'\nThe ACM Symposium on Virtual Reality Software and Technology (VRST) is a premier international symposium for the presentation of new research results, systems, and techniques among researchers and developers on augmented, virtual and mixed reality (AR/VR/MR, XR for short) software and technology.\r VRST brings together the main international research groups working on XR, along with many of the world\xe2\x80\x99s leading companies that provide or utilize XR systems. VRST 2022 will be held in Tsukuba, Japan, from Wednesday, Nov. 29th to Friday, Dec. 1st, 2022. The event is sponsored by ACM SIGCHI and SIGGRAPH.\r VRST 2022 welcomes paper submissions relating (but not limited) to the following areas:\r - VR/AR/MR(=XR) technology and devices\r- Advanced display technologies and immersive simulations\r- Low-latency and high-performance XR\r- Multi-user and distributed XR\r- XR software infrastructures and authoring systems\r- User interaction and collaborative interaction techniques for XR\r- Input devices for XR\r- Tracking and sensing for XR\r- Multisensory and multimodal system for XR\r- Brain-computer interfaces for XR\r- Haptics, smell, and taste interfaces for XR\r- Audio and music processing for XR\r- Sound synthesis and sonification for XR\r- Computer vision and computer graphics for XR\r- Immersive analytics\r- Modeling and simulation techniques\r- Rendering techniques for XR\r- Avatars and virtual humans\r- Tele-operation and telepresence\r- Performance testing, user experience, and empirical studies\r- Locomotion and navigation in virtual environments\r- Perception, presence, virtual embodiment, and cognition\r- Teleoperation and telepresence\r- Application of XR (e.g. training systems, medical systems, fabrication etc.)\r- Innovative HCI approaches in XR\r- Multi-disciplinary research projects involving innovative use of XR\r- XR System Contributions\r Important Dates\r- Abstracts due (title, abstract, author list): July 18, 2022, 23:59 AoE\r- Papers with all material submission deadline: July 22, 2022, 23:59 AoE\r- Posters and demos submission deadline: August 22, 2022, 23:59 AoE\r- Author notification papers: September 6, 2022\r- Revised papers, and posters/demos recommended from paper track: September 20, 2022\r- Final author notifications for all categories: September 27, 2022\r- Camera-ready papers due: October 11, 2022\r- Conference in Tsukuba, Japan + virtual (hybrid): Nov 29 - Dec 1, 2022\r Submission Information\r Details about the submission procedure can be found on the symposium website:\r- https://vrst.acm.org/vrst2022/submissions/\r Please use the ACM SIGCHI Conferences Submission System (PCS) to submit your work:\r- https://new.precisionconference.com/user/login\r Submission Guidelines:\r All accepted papers will be published in the ACM Digital Library in the VRST collection.\r Paper Format:\r Paper submissions (applied for Full papers and Short Papers) should be anonymous for a double-blind review process.  By contrast, Poster and Demo submissions do NOT have to be anonymous, and these submissions will be juried by committee members and receive light feedback (up to a few paragraphs in length). All submissions should be prepared in **a single column format**, using the Word or LaTeX templates from the official ACM Master article template packages and TAPS (see https://authors.acm.org/proceedings/production-information/taps-production-workflow). Authors should prepare their materials using numbered citations and references. See the TAPS webpage for guidance on how content length corresponds to the page limits for the final version.\r Submission Lengths:\r- Full paper: Up to a maximum of 9 pages double column excluding references.\r- Short paper: Up to a maximum of 4 pages excluding references.\r- Poster / Demo: Up to a maximum of 2 pages double column including references.\r Contacts\r Program Chairs\rpapers@vrst2022.org\r- Naoya Koizumi, The University of Electro-Communications\r- Haruka Matsukura, The University of Electro-Communications\r- Gerd Bruder, University of Central Florida\r- Daniel Roth, Friedrich-Alexander-Universitat Erlangen-Nurnberg\r- Kazuki Takashima, Tohoku University\r Poster and Demo Chairs\rposters@vrst2022.org\r- Takefumi Hiraki, University of Tsukuba\r- Yuki Ban, The University of Tokyo\r- Michal Piovarci, Institute of Science and Technology Austria\n\t'

title: b'Law and (in)justice  2023'
description: b'Mid-winter meeting of the Canadian Law and Society Association - Law and (in)justice in times of crisis'
Categories: b'law' b'law and society' b'legal studies'
Call For Papers: b'\nIn association with the midwinter meeting of the Canadian Law and Society Association, the Law and Society Program at Wilfrid Laurier University and the Department of Sociology and Legal Studies at the University of Waterloo are hosting a two-day, in-person conference on the theme of Law and (in)justice in times of crisis.\r From some perspectives, crises are everywhere, and are often intersecting: pandemic and irreversible climate catastrophes, unchecked racism and unending colonialism, democratic decline and gender backlash, economic meltdowns and mass surveillance. At the same time, there is no consensus on the nature of current crisis: not its meaning, nor cause, nor where responsibility lies, nor how to move forward. \r A declaration of crisis contains within it a demand for action, critique, and creativity. It challenges what is normal and taken-for-granted and all but requires us to consider ways of thinking or acting that represent a break with current routines, institutions, and relationships. In crises\xe2\x80\x99 demand for response, what possibilities are opened up, reshaped, and/or foreclosed?\r In such a context, what does it mean to talk of justice and injustice? And what is the place of law, as a root or anchor of the unacceptable status quo, a site of resistance, a map of ways through the moment, an opening for change of meaning, representation, or practice? Does talk of crisis distract from solving problems at hand, or invite renewal of familiar tools, concepts, methods, and/or approaches?\r As we gather in person on Wilfrid Laurier\xe2\x80\x99s Brantford campus on the lands of the Haudenosaunee, Anishnaawbe, and Neutral peoples, we invite scholars of law and society to come together to share work that intersects with our theme \xe2\x80\x93 including particularly, works in progress. We also welcome topics that do not fit directly into the central theme of the conference.\n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nAI in Government is hosting guest speaker Jeremy Golant, Government Solutions Consultant at Coursera presenting \xe2\x80\x98Driving Data Literacy in the Public Sector\xe2\x80\x99 on Wednesday, August 10, 2022 from 12 PM - 1 PM ET! \r As data becomes more seamlessly integrated within decision-making processes, public sector agencies must ensure individuals across the workforce can read, work with, and question data in the context of their role. Data literacy shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be mistaken for technical literacy, and it doesn\xe2\x80\x99t necessarily include the skills and knowledge needed by a data scientist. Rather, data literacy is now increasingly recognized as a core workforce competency and something that public sector agencies need to pay attention to. In this webinar, we\xe2\x80\x99ll explore the concept of data literacy, share the impact that a more data literate workforce can have on public sector agencies, and provide a roadmap for driving data skills development in your own organization. Be sure to stick around till the end for Q&A with Jeremy! title: b'FSW5G 2022'
description: b'The IEEE Federated Systems & Testbeds Workshop on 5G and Beyond  (FSW5G 2022) '
Categories: b'computer science' b'artificial intelligence' b'engineering' b'security'
Call For Papers: b'\nThe IEEE Federated Systems & Testbeds Workshop on 5G and Beyond (FSW5G 2022)\r5G and beyond networks will dramatically improve communications, latency, and enable a wide range of interactive and collaborative applications that are otherwise not possible.  The adoption of 5G and beyond networks paves the way for federated distributed platforms to provide critical end-to-end services, aiding in delivering innovative and transformative services to the Global Community. Adoption and development of such federated systems are subject to addressing several critical problems, including systems discovery, security issues, and 5G network slicing, to name a few.\r The IEEE Federated Systems & Testbeds Workshop on 5G and Beyond (FSW5G) will provide a high-profile, leading-edge forum for researchers and practitioners to present technical innovations, experimental results, theoretical studies, conceptual studies, and surveys on Federated System in 5G and Beyond. The goal of this workshop is to provide a forum for an interactive dialog between researchers in scientific domains and technologists and practitioners in the industry to discuss, promote, and demonstrate how recent developments in artificial intelligence, federated systems, and 5G (and beyond) systems can be used to integrate and explore various scientific and technological resources to solve critical world problems. We welcome original articles that have not published before on the following list of topics (not limited to):\r1.\tSystem federation design, setup, and management\r2.\tAutonomic management and orchestration for 5G Systems Federation\r3.\tAutonomic/Autonomous Networks (ANs) Federation Techniques\r4.\tFederation Techniques as Enablers for Agile Service Innovation and Delivery across multiple Domains\r5.\tFederated Systems Security Architectures and Controls\r6.\tFederated Testbeds for 5G and Beyond, design, analysis, and evaluation\r7.\tBlockchain and Non-Fungible Token (NFT) based techniques to control and manage 5G networks and services.\r8.\t5G and beyond Federated Testbeds Standardization Activities\r9.\tExperiments, testbeds, and prototyping systems for security.\r10.\tProtocols and APIs for Federated Autonomic Management & Control (AMC) operations across network domains\r11.\tFederation of Knowledge Planes (KPs) Platforms\r12.\tNetwork slicing security in 5G systems.\r13.\tTrusted computing for 5G systems.\r14.\tInterdisciplinary approaches for securing 5G systems.\r15.\t5G Applications Design and Performance Evaluation\r PAPER\rFull papers (a maximum of 6 pages in length) and posters (2 pages) are invited on a wide variety of topics relating to 5G and beyond as indicated above. Both full and poster must follow the official IEEE proceedings format. Both kinds of papers should be submitted via the Web submission form, available here. All manuscripts will be reviewed and judged on merits including originality, significance, interest, correctness, clarity, and relevance to the broader community. Papers are strongly encouraged to report experiences, measurements, and user studies, and to provide an appropriate quantitative evaluation. \r PROGRAM CO-CHAIRS\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tPratik Satam, Univ. of Arizona, USA\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tHisham Kholidy, State University of New York (SUNY) Polytechnic Institute, Utica, NY, USA\r ADVISORY COMMITTEE\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tSalim Hariri, Univ. of Arizona, USA\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tTaesang Choi, ETRI, South Korea\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tAbdella Battou, NIST, USA\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRobert Bohn, NIST, USA\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tTao Zhang, NIST, USA\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRanganai Chaparadza, Germany\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tMuslim Elkotob, Vodafone, Germany\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tSejun Song, Univ. of Missouri-Kansas City, USA \r\xe2\x80\xa2\tMoon-kook Park, Mobigen, South Korea\r SPONSORS\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tETRI, \r\xe2\x80\xa2\tMobigen,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tNSF Center for Cloud and Autonomic Computing, UArizona\r\n'

Call For Papers: b'\nWe cordially invite you to the International Workshop on Machine Learning and Quantum Computing Applications in Medicine and Physics, which will take place in Warsaw (Poland) from 13 to 16 September 2022. The workshop is organized by the National Centre for Nuclear Research in cooperation with scientists from the University of Vienna and Jagiellonian University.\r In the past two years, we have seen an increasing number of interdisciplinary exchanges, especially with machine learning methods involved. Many times similar techniques and tools are used to solve a variety of problems. This workshop aims to facilitate the transfer of knowledge by bringing together experts from various institutions and research groups in the field of medical imaging, radiotherapy, physics, and computer science. The workshop serves as a platform to enable research at the edge of various disciplines. The transfer of methods between disciplines is highly needed and it has repeatedly proved to be a very fruitful approach.\r The workshop will take place in KIG, Tr\xc4\x99backa street 4, in Old Town zone (Stare Miasto).\r  List of topics:\r* machine learning methods in medical applications,\r* machine learning methods in high-energy physics \xc9\x91nd astrophysics,\r* quantum machine learning,\r* Generative Adversarial Networks for fast simulations both in medicine \xc9\x91nd particle physics,\r* quantum simulations,\r* quantum \xc9\x91nd quantum-inspired computing algorithms,\r* novel methods in medical imaging,\r* High-Performance Computing (HPC) in physics \xc9\x91nd medicine, in particular on heterogeneous platforms such as FPGA \xc9\x91nd GPU.\r A training hands-on session will be held during the workshop. It will focus on applications of transfer learning methods.\r The workshop is planned to operate in an on-site format.\n\t'

title: b'GCA 2022'
description: b'The Seventh International Workshop on GPU Computing and AI'
Call For Papers: b"\n====================================================\rGCA'22: https://is-candar.org/GCA22/\r The Seventh International Workshop on GPU Computing and AI (GCA)\rhttps://is-candar.org/GCA22/\r to be held in conjunction with\r The Tenth International Symposium on Computing and Networking (CANDAR'22), \rHimeji, Hyogo, Japan, November 21-24, 2022\r https://is-candar.org/\r====================================================\r [Special announcement regarding COVID-19 situation]\r - We are working with the possibility of having a physical/hybrid/virtual meeting.\r - Regardless of physical/hybrid/virtual meeting, we will provide the opportunity to present the paper online for those not able to travel to Himeji for any reason. The details of online presentation will be informed later.\r - The review process will be conducted as in previous editions.\r - Regardless of physical/hybrid/virtual meeting, all accepted papers will be published on IEEE CPS as in previous years.\r  [Introduction]\rBuilt for massive parallelism, General Purpose computing on Graphic\rProcessing Unit (GPGPU) has superseded high-performance CPU in several\rimportant tasks, including computer graphics, physics calculations,\rencryption/decryption and scientific computations. Also, GPGPUs have \rbeen considered as a natural alternative to fulfill the computing \rneeds for Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning applications. \rRecent developments have shown intensive research activity in these \rfields.\r  The goal of this workshop is to provide a forum to discuss and\revaluate emerging techniques, platforms, and applications, capable of\rharvesting the power of current GPGPUs as well as sharing new ideas \rfrom the research area of Artificial Intelligence. \r The GCA workshop seeks for high-quality papers on various topics, \rincluding but not limited to: \r * GPU computing\r - GPU applications\r - Computer graphics on GPUs\r - GPU compilation\r - GPU programming environments\r - GPU power efficiency\r - GPU architectures\r - GPU theoretical computing models\r - GPU benchmarking/measurements\r - GPU embedded systems\r - Multi-GPU systems\r - GPU cluster\r - Heterogeneous GPU platforms\r - CPU-GPU cooperation\r - CUDA/OpenCL/OpenACC\r - Deep learning on GPUs\r * Artificial intelligence \r - Artificial neural networks\r - Big data analytics\r - Data mining\r - Deep learning\r - Experts systems\r - Fuzzy logic\r - Machine learning\r - Natural language processing\r - Computer vision\r - Reinforcement learning\r   [Paper format]\r* Regular paper: 5-7 pages\r* Poster paper: 3-4 pages\r [Publication]\rThe conference and workshop proceedings will be published by Conference \rPublishing Service and submitted to IEEE Xplore and CSDL digital libraries. \rAlso, they are submitted for indexing through INSPEC, EI (Compendex), \rThomson ISI, and other indexing services.\r [Important dates]\r * Abstract submission due: September 5, 2022 (extended, firm)\r * Paper submission due: September 10, 2022 (extended, firm)\r * Paper notification: October 1, 2022\r * Final camera-ready paper submission due: October 21, 2022\r * Workshop: November 21-24, 2022\r [Organizers]\r* Workshop co-chairs\r - Jacir L. Bordim (University of Brasilia)\r - Yasuaki Ito (Hiroshima University)\r [Program Committee]\r* Ulisses Rodrigues Afonseca (Federal Institute of Goi\xc3\xa1s-Brazil)\r* Eduardo Adilio Pelinson Alchieri (University of Bras\xc3\xadlia)\r* Hidetoshi Ando (University of Yamanashi)\r* Wei Der Chien (KTH Royal Institute of Technology)\r* Lucas Rodrigues Costa (University of Bras\xc3\xadlia)\r* Toshio Endo (Tokyo Institute of Technology)\r* Marcos Fagundes Caetano (University of Bras\xc3\xadlia)\r* Ken-ichi Fukui (Osaka University)\r* Takayasu Fushimi (Tokyo University of Technology)\r* Jing Gong (KTH Royal Institute of Technology)\r* Kohei Hatano (Kyushu University)\r* Tsutomu Inamoto (Ehime University)\r* Fumihiko Ino (Osaka University)\r* Kyeong Soo Kim (Xi'an Jiaotong-Liverpool University)\r* Atsushi Koike (National Institute of Technology, Ichinoseki College)\r* Kazuhiko Komatsu (Tohoku University)\r* Takahiro Nishigaki (Aoyama Gakuin University)\r* Yoshiaki Okubo (Hokkaido University)\r* Tomonobu Ozaki (Nihon University)\r* Max Plauth (Hasso Plattner Institute, University of Potsdam)\r* Hiroyuki Sato (The University of Tokyo)\r* Takashi Shimokawabe (The University of Tokyo)\r* Koichi Shirahata (FUJITSU LABORATORIES LTD.)\r* Nobuhiko Yamaguchi (Saga University)\r* Tetsuya Yoshida (Nara Women's University)\r* TBA\r\n"

title: b'ICEBE 2022'
description: b'The IEEE International Conference on e-Business Engineering'
Call For Papers: b'\nThe IEEE International Conference on e-Business Engineering (ICEBE) is a prestigious conference, and a flagship event. Since 2003, ICEBE has been provided as a high-quality international forum for researchers, engineers and business specialists to exchange the cutting-edge ideas, findings and experiences of e-business.\r Constant evolution in IT technologies have enabled enterprises to use e-business and its applications in a variety of areas, such as developing innovative business models, developing new marketing and sales channel, having the ability of rapid sense-and-response, etc. However, before such applications can be developed and their benefits realised, enterprises need to address the challenging tasks of first using various existing complex technologies to build such systems and then adapt to the changed computing paradigm, while remaining competitive. Based on these essential complexities in e-business, ICEBE 2022 invites papers from researchers and practitioners that focusses on the aforementioned areas and looks at them from an extensive coverage of system, software, service and business.\r All of the accepted and presented papers in the conference will be included in the conference proceedings published by IEEE Computer Society. The proceedings will be submitted for inclusion in the IEEE Xplore Digital Library and will also be submitted to EI and INSPEC for indexing.\r We invite submissions of high-quality papers describing fully developed results or on-going foundational and applied work on the following topics:\r Agent for e-Business Track\r - Agent-mediated e-commerce systems\r- Agent-based artificial markets\r- Trading, negotiation, auction and mechanism design\r- Collective decision making and coordination for e-Business\r- Trust and reputation in online agent systems\r- Personal agents and recommender systems\r- Agent based web mining, text mining and information retrieval\r- Agent or actor oriented analysis in social networks\r Big Data for e-Business Track\r - Data and knowledge engineering for e-business\r- Workflow and business process tools and management for e-business\r- Semantic Web, Web 2.0, and business intelligence\r- Stream processing, complex event processing and continuous queries\r- E-business marketing, data mining, and relationship management\r- Machine learning, cybernetics, and agents for e-business services management\r- Knowledge management and e-learning\r- Big data and super computing\r- Big data analytics for e-business\r- Super computing and simulation of e-businesses\r- Applications of super computing\r Internet of Things (IoT) Track\r - Legal perspectives in IoT-based business service\r- IoS (Internet of Services) plus IoT\r- New business models and value map\r- Auto-organization on context, exchange or supply chain\r- Architectures and platforms of IoT applications\r- Machine learning and Evolutionary Computing for IoT applications\r- Edging/Cloud Computing for Smart IoT\r- Smart manufacturing and Industrial IoT\r- Smart cities and internet of vehicles\r- Control and decision making for smart IoT\r- Security and privacy for smart IoT\r- Mobile and Autonomous Computing Track\r- Mobile and pervasive methods, applications and integrated solutions\r- Sensor systems and RFID applications\r- Ubiquitous content access\r- Context awareness and smart environments\r- Resource discovery of mobile services\r- 3G technology and services for e-business\r- Social networks and social behavior modeling in mobile commerce\r Security, Privacy, and Blockchain Track\r - Security, privacy and trust methods and solutions for enabling e-business\r- Open source technologies and components for e-business\r- Open source version management\r- Authentication in e-business\r- Blockchain security models\r- Blockchain architectures for efficient processing\r- Service-Oriented and Cloud Track\r- Service process modeling\r- Service quality assurance\r- Service design methodology\r- Service optimization\r- Service composition\r- Service QoS optimization\r- Service security\r- Service requirement collection, specification, and analysis\r- Data- and computation-intensive services\r- Business intelligence and analytics for services\r- XaaS (X as a service including Iaas, PaaS, SaaS)\r- Infrastructure as a Service, Platform as a Service, Application as a Service\r- Extreme scalability, high availability, elasticity, and reliability in a cloud\r- Multi-tenancy, security and privacy in clouds\r- Programming models and transaction models for the cloud\r- Cloud business support services and operational support\r Software Engineering for e-Business Track\r - Design methods, tools and science for e-business\r- Models, platforms and applications for e-business\r- Components, services and solutions for e-business\r- Aspects of green business and green commerce\r- Cloud and mobile software engineering\r- Service-oriented software engineering\r Ecommerce Trading Technologies Track\r - Online credit and reputation evaluation\r- Electronic contract\r- Electronic invoice\r- Internet Finance/Manufacturing/Farm\r- Ecommerce services and infrastructure\r- Monitoring and supporting services for Ecommerce\r- Ecommerce laws and standards\r- Applications of blockchain\r- Industry Track: Deliver the Intelligent Enterprise\r- Analytics with Big Data\r- Industry 4.0 and Smart Manufacturing\r- Internet of Things\r- Enterprise usage with Machine Learning\r- Trusted and traceable network with Blockchain\r Special Session: Digital Games as Socio-Technical Systems\r - Games as e-business and games as a service\r- Games for education/vocational training/medical therapy\r- Games for entertainment\r- Games as internet of things\r- Games as audio-visual systems\r- Game balancing\r- Game development as a creative process\n\t'

title: b'Taxonomic Variability 2022'
description: b'Taxonomic Variability and Morphometrics in Early Vertebrates'
Call For Papers: b'\nA PeerJ Life and Environment Special Issue highlighting the latest research focusing on the variability and evolution of early vertebrates\r Special Issue Editors: \r Graciela Pi\xc3\xb1eiro, Adjunct Professor, Universidad de la Rep\xc3\xbablica\r Michel Laurin, CNRS Senior Research Scientist, CR2P, CNRS/MNHN/UPMC\r Pablo Nu\xc3\xb1ez Demarco, Assistant Professor, Universidad de la Rep\xc3\xbablica\r In Paleontology, several iconic taxa are represented by many specimens, but their low-level systematics remains poorly understood or controversial; recent examples that have been investigated include mesosaurs and sphenacodontids, but also iconic taxa such as Ichthyosaurus and Tyrannosaurus.\r Morphometrics is useful to quantify variability and potentially, to assess the influence of ontogenetic, ecological and environmental factors (which leave indirect clues in the fossil record). These produce intraspecific variability that can be mistaken for taxonomically significant variation. Recent contributions in this field have demonstrated how the application of morphometrics can be relevant to evolutionary studies of problematic taxa, highlighting and encouraging the development of this kind of interdisciplinary study. Stratigraphic analysis allows specimens to be arranged in time to record chronological changes, while revisions and redescriptions clarify the status of various materials, identifying weak points in the descriptions and raising new questions.\r This Special Issue will contain papers that focus on the variability and evolution of early vertebrates, especially for taxa that are well-represented in the fossil record but include specimens that are poorly preserved, which hampers definition of diagnostic characters. We encourage submissions of primary research papers, especially those on the taxonomic variability in ancient (Paleozoic and Mesozoic) vertebrate clades, focusing on methodologies such as morphometrics, stratigraphic and/or comparative analyses, as well as taxonomic revisions or redescriptions.\r This Special Issue will be among the first compilations of novel data for determining the presence and origin of morphological, ontogenetic and evolutionary variability in a wide range of vertebrate taxa, which can be reproduced in future contributions.\r For more information and to submit your abstract, please visit:  https://peerj.com/special-issues/109-morphometrics \n\t'

title: b'S&REHIS 2022'
description: b'THE 6TH INTERNATIONAL WORKSHOP ON SECURITY AND RELIABILITY OF eHEALTH INFORMATION SYSTEMS'
Categories: b'computer science' b'healthcare informatics' b'artificial intelligence' b'security'
Call For Papers: b'\nHealth Informatics presents complex and challenging issues to computer scientists, social scientists, law experts, and policy makers. Appropriate healthcare informatics provisioning involves processing specialized user centric knowledge that is private and of sensitive nature. Electronic health record systems provide opportunities for information sharing which promise to improve healthcare services, for both healthcare providers and healthcare seekers. However, appropriate information management measures are essential for privacy preservation and reliability.\rTraditional measures may not be suitable for eHealth systems because, in eHealth systems,  the roles of all stakeholders are not well defined. Healthcare professionals require ready access to as much information as possible to support informed decision making. However, patients may want to exercise control over the entities granting controlled access to their personal health information, with particular concerns for information privacy. Balancing these competing concerns is a major challenge in the implementation of successful e-Health systems.\rThis workshop will focus on the major challenge in Health Informatics. We seek papers addressing the following issues in e-Health systems but are not limited to:\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Role of Big Data in eHealthcare\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Role of Internet of Things in eHealthcare\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Access Control\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Vulnerability assessment\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Mobile Identity management\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Authentication, security access policies\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Privacy-respecting Authentication\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Privacy issues in the Internet of Things\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Privacy issues in wireless networks\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Security Management of M2M network\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Testing and verification of eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Simulation based methods in eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Security and Privacy issues in eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Formal methods in eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Verification of eHealth software and equipment\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Performance evaluation of eHealth systems\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Open issues, surveys on eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Secured network architectures for eHealth\r\xe2\x80\xa2 eHeathcare Forensics and Investigation\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Remote and wireless-based Biometrics system\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Mobile malware\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Mobile botnets\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Security and privacy issues in Smartphones\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Intrusion and fraud detection\r\xe2\x80\xa2 Socio-economic issues\r HEALTHCOM2022 CONFERENCE GENERAL CHAIR\rFabio Lavagetto, University of Genoa, Italy\rFranco Fontana, Esaote S.p.A., Italy\r HEALTHCOM2022 CONFERENCE TECHNICAL PROGRAM CHAIRS\rAndrea Sciarrone, University of Genoa, Italy\rHsi-Pin Ma, National Tsing Hua University, Taiwan\r S&REHIS 2022 Track Chairs\rKashif Saleem, Center of Excellence in Information Assurance (CoEIA), King Saud University, Saudi Arabia - title: b'A-VB 2022'
description: b'ACII 2022 Affective Vocal Burst Workshop and Competition '
Call For Papers: b'\nWithin this first iteration of the ACII A-VB Challenge, the participants are presented with four emotion-focused sub-challenges that utilize the large-scale and \xe2\x80\x9cin-the-wild\xe2\x80\x9d Hume-VB dataset. The dataset and the four tracks draw attention to new innovations in emotion science as it pertains to vocal expression, addressing low- and high-dimensional theories of emotional expression, cultural variation, and \xe2\x80\x9ccall types\xe2\x80\x9d (laugh, cry, sigh, etc.). The four tasks include:\r **The High-Dimensional Emotion Task (A-VB High)**: The A-VB High track, explores a high-dimensional emotion space for understanding vocal bursts. Participants will be challenged with predicting the intensity of 10 emotions (Awe, Excitement, Amusement, Awkwardness, Fear, Horror, Distress, Triumph, Sadness, and Surprise) associated with each vocal burst as a multi-output regression task. Participants will report the average Concordance Correlation Coefficient (CCC), as well as the Pearson correlation coefficient, across all 10 emotions. The baseline for this challenge will be based on CCC.\r **The Two-Dimensional Emotion Task (A-VB Two)**: In the A-VB Two track, we investigate a low-dimensional emotion space that is based on the circumplex model of affect. Participants will predict values of arousal and valence (on a scale from 1=unpleasant/subdued, 5=neutral, 9=pleasant/stimulated) as a regression task. Participants will report the average Concordance Correlation Coefficient (CCC), as well as the Pearson correlation coefficient, across the two dimensions. The baseline for this challenge will be based on CCC.\r **The Cross-Cultural Emotion Task (A-VB Culture)**: In the A-VB Culture track, participants will be challenged with predicting the intensity of 10 emotions associated with each vocal burst as a multi-output regression task, using a model or multiple models that generate predictions specific to each of the four cultures  (the U.S., China, Venezuela, or South Africa). Specifically, annotations of each vocal burst will consist of culture-specific ground truth, meaning that the ground truth for each sample will be the average of annotations solely from the country of origin of the sample. Participants will report the average Concordance Correlation Coefficient (CCC), as well as the Pearson correlation coefficient, across all 10 emotions. The baseline for this challenge will be based on CCC.\r **The Expressive Burst-Type Task (A-VB Type)**: In the A-VB Type task, participants will be challenged with classifying the type of expressive vocal burst from 7 classes (Gasp, Laugh, Cry, Scream, Grunt, Groan, Pant, Other).  Participants will report the Unweighted Average Recall (UAR) as a measure of performance.\rThe A-VB Workshop will also be accepting contributions on other related topics:\r Detecting and Understanding Nonverbal Vocalizations\r*Modeling Vocal Emotional Expression\r*Cross-Cultural Emotional Expression Modeling\r*Other topics related to Auditory Affective Computing\r  The general deadlines have been extended and are as follows:\r*Challenge Opening (data available): May 27, 2022\r*Baselines information released: TBA.\r*Other Topics contributions deadline: July 22, 2022\r(Included in ACII Proceedings)\r*Notification of Acceptance: July 29, 2022\r*Camera Ready: August 15, 2022\r*Competition deadline: September 2, 2022\r*Competition Technical Report submission deadline: September 6, 2022\r(Peer Reviewed by A-VB technical committee, not included in ACII Proceedings)\r*Notification of Acceptance: September 16, 2022\r*Workshop: October 18 - 21, 2022\n\t'

title: b'SoS 2022'
description: b'Secure Our Streets'
Call For Papers: b'\nSecure Our Streets (SOS) is a conference aiming to provide a global platform for information exchange among industry experts and researchers in the domain of automotive security and privacy technology. The goal of the conference is to enable the community of automotive OEMs, providers, academic researchers, policy makers, and government regulators to showcase the recent advances and challenges in areas of automotive security and privacy technologies, organizational strategy and cybersecurity plan and government policies.\r We are inviting presentations of recent advances in the area of automotive security and privacy including technology, organizational strategies, implementation of policy and regulations, methodologies, use-case demonstrations, challenges and future directions. \r Topics of Interest (Not limited to)\r===================================\r * Security and risk management and frameworks for vehicular systems, automated driving s systems\r* Processes, methods, application of tools for automotive security\r* Incident response and forensics for the automotive domain\r* Architectures for security and privacy in future autonomous vehicular systems, electric vehicles, V2X networks\r* Security implications of future networking technology in the automotive domain(e.g. 5G)\r* Supply chain security for automotive systems\r* Security of off-road vehicles and commercial vehicles\r* Security best practices for next generation automotive systems\r* Privacy aspects of automotive data economy\r* Legal and regulatory aspects for automotive security and privacy\r* Future of automotive security \xe2\x80\x93 Blockchain, Robust AI systems, PQC for automotive, data management infrastructure, road infrastructure\r Submission Process\r===================\rWe accept:\r Short abstracts (presentation/demos/posters)\rResults of work-in progress\rComplete and published works\r  Process\r=========\r Submit paper / idea / presentation for review. Content must not be complete at this time, however an abstract must be submitted.\r[Submission Ready] All submissions will be reviewed by the CFP Review Committee.\rDuring the review process, non-compliant submissions will be notified of non-compliance when reviewed.\rNotification of acceptance\r[Live-Ready] Submission of updated and complete Presentation files\rThe proceedings will be published by SOS and ASRG.\r  Requirements\r============ \r Submissions must have a real name, no aliases.\rDisclosure presentations in which the affected companies have not been informed, will not be considered. The reason for this conference is not fame, but to inform.\rSubmissions may only be entered by researchers/speakers (no submissions from PR firms/marketing representatives).\rProduct or vendor-related pitches can only take place in Sponsor Booths.\rSubmissions must clearly detail concepts, ideas, findings, and solutions a researcher or speaking team plans to present.\rSubmissions that highlight new research, tools, vulnerabilities, etc. will be given priority.\rSubmissions that include White Papers are highly encouraged and will also be given priority.\rIncomplete Submissions will not be considered.\rIndividuals may submit more than one proposal, but each proposal must be submitted via a separate submission form.\rEach submission must include detailed biographies of the proposed speaking team.\rSubmitters will be contacted directly if Review Board members have any questions about a submission.\rPresentations and videos will be published sometime after the conference, unless the submitter requests specifically not to be published.\rTo request work not to be published after the conference must be done at time of submission or per email before the conference. Requests after the conference will not be considered.\r  Pre-Recorded Videos\r--------------------\rSince this conference is international and the worldwide infrastructure and scheduling issues can have an impact on the quality of the presented content at the conference, we require that all presentations be pre-recorded.  Presentations can be also live, however a pre-recorded video is still required.\r Videos must be at least HD quality.\n\t'

title: b'SNR 2022'
description: b'The 8th International Workshop on Symbolic-Numeric Methods for Reachability Analysis'
Categories: b'formal methods' b'verification' b'cyber-physical systems' b'reinforcement learning'
Call For Papers: b'\n=========\r Description\r=========\rHybrid systems are complex dynamical systems that combine discrete and continuous components. Reachability questions, regarding whether a system can run into a certain subset of its state space, stand at the core of verification and synthesis problems for hybrid systems. Successful reachability analysis methods for hybrid systems require the unification of techniques from at least two research areas:\r )) Symbolic methods that operate on exact and discrete representations of systems, in the form of various model checking and theorem proving algorithms.\r)) Numerical methods that operate on various forms of numerical approximations and continuous transformations of the systems, as developed in the area of continuous dynamical systems and control theory. \r The existing, successful solutions for reachability analysis for hybrid dynamical systems cleverly integrate symbolic and numerical reasoning to tackle the scalability challenge. For instance, the reachable set computation methods explicitly construct flow-pipes that numerically overapproximate the reachable states over time, while efficient computation of such overapproximations requires symbolic representations such as support functions. Similarly, constraint solving methods symbolically encode reachability properties as logic formulas, while solving such formulas requires numerically-driven decision procedures. The key goal of the Symbolic and Numerical Methods for Reachability Analysis (SNR) workshop is to provide a platform to further explore synergies among these approaches by bringing together the experts in these two domains.\r =====\rScope\r=====\rThe SNR workshop aims to catalyze work on the interface of symbolic and numerical methods for the reachability analysis. The scope of the workshop includes, but is not restricted to, the following topics:\r **  Verification of hybrid systems\r**    Symbolic representation of regions in reachability analysis\r**    Techniques for Flow-pipe construction\r**    Abstraction techniques for hybrid systems and numerical programs\r**    Trajectory/Counterexample generation from symbolic paths\r**    Techniques for reliable integration\r **   Decision procedures supporting real numbers\r   ** Formal logics to reason about hybrid systems\r**    Symbolic and Numerical Methods for Reinforcement Learning and Planning\r  **  Domain specific approaches in Biology, Robotics, and Cyber-Physical Systems \r This year, the organizers encourage submissions of papers exploring the intersection of SNR and Machine-Learning (ML). Machine Learning (ML) algorithms and data-driven components are at the core of modern engineering applications of hybrid dynamical systems providing support for perception and adaptation. Moreover, the recent successes of Deep Neural Networks (DNN) and Reinforcement Learning (RL) hint at powerful approaches to tackle scalability challenges in SNR. We invite research papers at the intersection of SNR and ML on the following non-exhaustive list of topics:\r **    Reinforcement Learning (RL) for Real-Time and Hybrid Systems,\r**    Formal Logics for Continuous-State RL (e.g., formal specifications in RL, shielding for RL),\r**    Decision Procedures for Continuous-State RL (e.g. SAT/SMT approaches to infer reward machines),\r**    Deep Neural networks for Symbolic and Numerical Reasoning for Reachability (e.g., neural certificates),\r**    Supervised Learning for SNR (e.g., using decision-trees in generating human-interpretable policies),\r**    Unsupervised Learning for SNR (e.g., mining formal specifications from behaviors), and\r**    Applications of SNR in safety-critical machine learning. \r The topic of the workshop has direct connections with the conferences within the CONFEST (e.g., FORMATS and CONCUR) and we believe that participants of the main conference may be interested in attending SNR and vice-versa. The workshop format is intended to complement the main conference by providing an informal meeting place specifically for researchers involved in the projects requiring the background both in symbolic and numerical verification. \r ================\rSubmission Information\r================\r The workshop solicits\r **    long research papers (not exceeding 15 pages excluding references),\r**    short research papers (not exceeding 6 pages excluding references) and\r**    work-in-progress papers (not exceeding 6 pages excluding references). \r Research papers must present original unpublished work which is not submitted elsewhere. In order to foster the exchange of ideas, we also encourage work-in-progress papers, which present recent or on-going work. The papers should be written in English and formatted according to the EPTCS guidelines. Papers can be submitted using the EasyChair system. All submissions will undergo a peer-reviewing process.\r Accepted research papers will be presented at the workshop and will be published in the Electronic Proceedings in Theoretical Computer Science (EPTCS). Accepted work-in-progress papers will be presented at the workshop but will not be included in the proceedings. \n\t'
