title: b'DISC 2022'
description: b'DISC 2022 : 36th International Symposium on Distributed Computing'
Call For Papers: b'\nCall for Papers\r 36th International Symposium on Distributed Computing\rOctober 25-27, 2022\rAugusta, Georgia, USA\r Submission server: https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=disc2022\rDates\r     Submission (regular papers and brief announcements): May 13, 2022 (23:59 AoE)\r    Rebuttal phase (regular papers and brief announcements): June 29- July 4, 2022 (23:59 AoE)\r    Notification (regular papers): July 25, 2022\r    Notification (brief announcements): July 25, 2022\r    Final version for proceedings: August 12, 2022\r Scope\r Submissions are sought in all areas of distributed algorithms and\rdistributed systems including theory, design, implementation,\rmodelling, analysis, and application of distributed systems and\rnetworks. Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\r     Biological and nature-inspired distributed algorithms\r    Blockchain protocols\r    Coding and reliable communication\r    Communication networks: algorithms, protocols, and applications\r    Complexity, lower bounds, and impossibility results\r    Design and analysis of distributed algorithms\r    Distributed and concurrent data structures\r    Distributed algorithms for clouds and IoT\r    Distributed graph algorithms\r    Distributed machine learning and data science\r    Distributed operating systems, middleware, database systems\r    Distributed resource management\r    Fault tolerance, reliability, self-organization, self-stabilization\r    Formal methods for distributed computing: verification, synthesis and testing\r    Game-theoretic and knowledge-based approaches to distributed computing\r    Internet and web applications, social networks and recommendation systems\r    Massively-parallel, high-performance, cloud and grid computing\r    Mobile agents, autonomous distributed systems, swarm robotics\r    Multiprocessor and multi-core architectures and algorithms\r    Overlay networks and peer-to-peer networks\r    Population protocols and chemical reaction networks\r    Quantum distributed algorithms\r    Replication, consensus, and consistency\r    Security in distributed computing, cryptographic protocols\r    Synchronization, persistence and transactional memory\r    Wireless, mobile, sensor and ad-hoc networks\r Submissions\r Papers are to be submitted electronically at https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=disc2022.\r A submitted paper should clearly motivate the importance of the problem being addressed, discuss prior work and its relationship to the paper, explicitly and precisely state the paper\xe2\x80\x99s key contributions, and outline the key technical ideas and methods used to achieve the main claims. A submission should strive to be accessible to a broad audience, as well as having sufficient details for experts in the area.\r There are two types of submissions: regular papers and brief announcements. Regular papers must report on original research that has not previously been published (and may not be concurrently submitted to other journals or conferences with proceedings). All ideas necessary for an expert to fully verify the central claims in a paper, including experimental results, should be included in the submission. A brief announcement may describe work in progress or work presented elsewhere. A brief announcement may also present a result that is short and elegant, but does not require a longer paper. It may also be used to announce a software distribution or an experimental results of interest that can be concisely described.\rSubmission format\r Submissions must be in English in pdf format and they must be prepared using the LaTeX style template for LIPIcs (https://submission.dagstuhl.de/series/details/5#author) with\r \\documentclass[a4paper,anonymous,USenglish]{lipics-v2021}.\r Submissions must be anonymous, without any author names, affiliations, or email addresses. The contact information of the authors will be entered separately in Easychair.\r For regular papers, there is no page limit, and authors are encouraged to use the \xe2\x80\x9cfull version\xe2\x80\x9d of their paper as the submission. The initial 15 pages should contain a clear presentation of the merits of the paper, including a discussion of the paper\xe2\x80\x99s importance within the context of prior work and a description of the key technical and conceptual ideas used to achieve its main claims. (Illustrative figures are encouraged.) The submission must contain full proofs of all claims in the paper.\r Although there is no bound on the length of a submission, material other than the first 15 pages will be read at the committee\xe2\x80\x99s discretion. Papers submitted as brief announcements should comply with the above rules, replacing 15 pages with 5 pages.\r Submissions not conforming to the submission guidelines and papers outside of the scope of the conference will be rejected without consideration.\rAnonymous Submissions\r We will use a relaxed implementation of double-blind peer review. Submissions must not reveal the identity of the authors in any way. In particular, authors\xe2\x80\x99 names and affiliation should not appear in the document itself. Authors should ensure that any references to their own related work are in the third person (e.g., not \xe2\x80\x9cWe build on our previous work \xe2\x80\xa6\xe2\x80\x9d but rather \xe2\x80\x9cWe build on the work of \xe2\x80\xa6\xe2\x80\x9d). The purpose of this process is to help PC members and external reviewers come to an initial judgment about the paper without bias, not to make it impossible for them to discover the authors if they were to try.\r You are free to disseminate your work through arXiv and other online repositories and give presentations on your work as usual. Moreover, nothing should be done in the name of anonymity that weakens the submission or makes the job of reviewing the paper more difficult. In particular, important references should not be omitted or anonymized.\r Brief announcements should also be submitted without author names and affiliations so that a reviewer can form an initial judgment without bias, but they can contain a reference to the full version of the work in the bibliography.\r Authors with further questions on double-blind reviewing are encouraged to contact the PC chair by email.\r Please feel free to ask the PC chair if you have any questions about the double-blind policy of DISC 2022.\rConflict of Interest\r The submission form provides an opportunity to specify conflicts of interest with any of the PC members. If you feel that you have a valid reason for a conflict of interest beyond the PC members, or any other issues related to the fair treatment of your submission, contact the PC chair, Christian Scheideler, or the SafeTOC representative for DISC, Faith Ellen.\rPublication\r The proceedings will be published by LIPIcs. The final version of the paper has to be formatted following the LIPIcs guidelines. Regular papers will have 15 pages in the final proceedings (excluding the front page, the references, and a brief appendix of up to 5 pages), and brief announcements will have 3 pages in the proceedings (including everything). If more space is needed, the authors are encouraged to post the full version e.g. on arXiv and refer to it in their paper.\r Accepted papers and brief announcements must be presented by one of the authors, with a full registration and according to the final schedule. Any submission accepted into the technical program but not presented on-site will be withdrawn from the final proceedings.\rAwards\r Awards will be given to the best paper and the best student paper. To be eligible for the best student paper award at least one of the paper authors must be a full-time student at the time of submission, and the student(s) must have made a significant contribution to the paper.\r Program/Steering/Organizing Committees\r  \n'

Call For Papers: b'\norganized by the European Scientific Institute, ESI, in cooperation with its partner universities. It hosts PhD holders who are interested in upgrading their academic careers by working on a specific research topic in a multidisciplinary environment and the developing area of computer sciences and engineering; agriculture, astronomy, botany, zoology, ecology, biology, chemistry, earth sciences, mathematics, physics, medicine, and their sub-domains.\r The ESI postdoctoral program will enhance the mobility of academic staff and strengthen academic cooperation through ESI Masterclasses, work under the guidance of an academic advisor, working in research groups, research visit at one of the host Universities, guest lectures, and joint publications of research articles. It will contribute to knowledge sharing and sharing of best practices among candidates, their research advisers as well as the ESI network of experts.\r  Languages of the program are English and Spanish.\r In times full of challenges with the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, the world, more than ever, needs further scientific discoveries. Every selected fellow will deal with a specific societal challenge through attending masterclasses while leaving time for guided research. The interdisciplinary cooperation of the program is provided through academic activities with researchers from different universities and academic backgrounds.\r https://www.esipostdoc.net/\rpostdoc@euinstitute.net\r  \n'

title: b'FTSCS 2022'
description: b'8th International Workshop on Formal Techniques for Safety-Critical Systems'
Categories: b'formal methods' b'software engineering' b'verification' b'industrial applications'
Call For Papers: b'\n---------------------------------------------------------------------\r                      Call for Papers\r                          FTSCS 2022\r 8th International Workshop on Formal Techniques for Safety-Critical Systems\r          Auckland, New Zealand, December 7, 2022\r             (an OOPSLA/SPLASH 2022 workshop)\r         https://2022.splashcon.org/home/ftscs-2022\r ---------------------------------------------------------------------\r *** ACM Digital Library proceedings ***\r*** Science of Computer Programming special issue ***\r Submission deadline: September 1, 2022\r  Aims and Scope:\r There is an increasing demand for using formal methods to validate and\rverify safety-critical systems in fields such as power generation and\rdistribution, avionics, automotive systems, medical systems, and\rautonomous vehicles. In particular, newer standards, such as DO-178C\r(avionics), ISO 26262 (automotive systems), IEC 62304 (medical\rdevices), and CENELEC EN 50128 (railway systems), emphasize the need\rfor formal methods and model-based development, thereby speeding up\rthe adaptation of such methods in industry.\r The aim of this workshop is to bring together researchers and engineers\rwho are interested in the application of formal and semi-formal methods\rto improve the quality of safety-critical computer systems. FTSCS\rstrives to promote research and development of formal methods and\rtools for industrial applications, and is particularly interested in\rindustrial applications of formal methods. \r Specific topics include, but are not limited to:\r * case studies and experience reports on the use of formal methods for\r  analyzing safety-critical systems, including avionics, automotive,\r  medical, railway, and other kinds of safety-critical and\r  QoS-critical systems \r* methods, techniques and tools to support automated analysis,\r  certification, debugging, etc., of safety/QoS-critical systems\r* analysis methods that address the limitations of formal methods in\r  industry (usability, scalability, etc.)\r* formal analysis support for modeling languages used in industry,\r  such as AADL, Ptolemy, SysML, SCADE, Modelica, etc.\r* code generation from validated models.\r The workshop will provide a platform for discussions and the exchange of\rinnovative ideas, so submissions on work in progress are encouraged.\r  Submission:\r We solicit submissions reporting on:\r A- original research contributions (10 pages max, ACM format);\rB- applications and experiences (10 pages max, ACM format);\rC- surveys, comparisons, and state-of-the-art reports (10 pages max, ACM);\rD- tool papers (5 pages max, ACM format);\rE- position papers and work in progress (5 pages max, ACM format)\r related to the topics mentioned above.\r(The page limits do not include the references.)\r All submissions must be original, unpublished, and not submitted\rconcurrently for publication elsewhere. Paper submission is done\rvia HotCRP at https://ftscs-2022.hotcrp.com/.\rSubmissions should be prepared in LaTeX, adhering to\rthe ACM format available at\rhttps://www.acm.org/publications/proceedings-template using the\r"sigplan" option.\r  Publication:\r All accepted papers will appear in the pre-proceedings of FTSCS 2022.\rAccepted papers in the title: b'GCSR 2023'
description: b'Special Issue: Greenwashing in Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR)'
Call For Papers: b'\nBackground and Motivation\rThe world today is facing major grand challenges such as global warming, environmental pollution, and labor rights violations. Governments and the public around the world are paying closer attention to these issues and calling on companies to actively engage in Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR), while shifting from the pursuit of pure economic interests to tackling broader social and environmental issues (Carroll & Shabana, 2010; P\xc3\xa9rez et al., 2019). Especially the Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) outbreak has not only brought threats to the lives and health of people all over the world, but also engendered great uncertainty in relation to the development of the global economy. As the epidemic continues to spread globally, the economic development of some economies has stagnated or even regressed, which has aggravated existing grand challenges (Jamali et al., 2021). In this context, the public has higher expectations than ever for companies to fulfill their social responsibilities (He & Harris, 2020). Many companies have also actively contributed to the fight against the epidemic, fulfilling their CSR mandate through charitable donations, the establishment of anti\xef\xbf\xbeepidemic funds, and participation in the production of anti-epidemic supplies. But there are real concerns and questions about the willingness of companies to continue to engage in CSR despite the economic hardships and recessions most countries are now facing, and the extent to which they will resist (or not) the temptation for \xe2\x80\x9cgreenwashing\xe2\x80\x9dto save face and maintain a positive public image. \rIn the field of CSR research, the issue of greenwashing has received increasing \rattention. As an abnormal and faking social responsibility behavior (Gatti et al., 2019), greenwashing means the firm exhibits excessive whitewashing in environmental \rprotection publicity, charitable donations, employee welfare and other social \rresponsibilities and exaggerates or falsely discloses deceiving information pertaining \rto CSR implementation (Li et al., 2015). From the perspective of subjective initiative \ror conscious activities of firms, the main reason for greenwashing behaviors is that the \rbenefits brought by publicizing CSR can lead to changes in consumer perceptions and \rimproved public image and competitive positioning (Shea & Hawn, 2019; Chen & Chang, 2013). According to the view of corporate citizenship theory (Moon et al., 2005), \rcorporate citizenship refers to a firm\xe2\x80\x99s responsibilities toward society, the \xe2\x80\x9csocial person\xe2\x80\x9d attributes of moral and ethical firms require them to be responsible for social welfare and development and to establish a responsible image as corporate citizens. However, due to limited resources and intensifying pressures from stakeholders and society, firms may share or publicize CSR information that may show inconsistencies between reality and presumed behavior (Scheidler et al., 2019), which results in turn in perceptions of greenwashing and hypocrisy (Jauernig et al., 2021). To a certain extent, greenwashing behavior is regarded as a kind of negative CSR implementation, that is seemingly conformable, yet disobedient and deceitful in essence.\rFurthermore, various scholars conducted exploratory studies on issues such as the \rcharacteristics of firms that engage in greenwashing behavior (Yang et al., 2020), the \rmarket response and economic consequences of CSR greenwashing behavior (Guo et al., 2017), the identification of CSR greenwashing behavior (Siano et al., 2017) and the \rgovernance mechanism of CSR greenwashing behavior (Kim & Lyon, 2015). Important \rfindings are obtained such as, in terms of enterprise characteristics of greenwashing \rbehavior, enterprises that have short-term economic performance pressure (Kim et al., 2021), or intend to build a positive image to deal with internal and external pressure,\rare more likely to engage in greenwashing behavior (Quan et al., 2018); With respect \rto the economic consequences of greenwashing behavior, the continued existence of \rCSR greenwashing behavior can disrupt market order, reduce public trust and also \raffect firm\xe2\x80\x99s own development (Fassin & Buelens, 2011); Concerning the identification \rof greenwashing behavior, Terra Choice (2009) proposed seven forms of greenwashing \rbehavior (The Seven Sins of Greenwashing) which has since been regarded as the \rstandard for identifying CSR greenwashing behavior (de Freitas Netto et al., 2020); \rRegarding the governance mechanism of greenwashing behavior, social media, intra\xef\xbf\xbefirm CSR management mechanism and the rating mechanism by third-parties can effectively govern CSR greenwashing behavior (Lyon & Maxwell, 2011; Lyon & Montgomery, 2013, 2015). Greenwashing behavior can also show a strong effect of misleading information on stakeholders (Uyar et al., 2020), affecting their decision\xef\xbf\xbemaking results and efficiency, which can make it difficult for stakeholders to judge whether the CSR behavior is \xe2\x80\x9ctruly green\xe2\x80\x9d or involves greenwashing (Ruiz-Blanco et al., 2022). Furthermore, the existence of the stigma of greenwashing (Kawamura and Kusumi, 2020) can make CSR, which is originally a charitable and noble deed, to be a thankless and irrelevant endeavor.\rIt is important at this point to gain a better understanding of greenwashing and \rwhat it entails and to shed light on the theoretical underpinnings for this widespread \rphenomenon, as well as related similar concepts such as corporate hypocrisy (Wagner \ret al., 2020), corporate pseudo-social responsibility (Zhao et al., 2020), and CSR \rdecoupling (Jamali & Karam, 2018). In fact, existing theoretical insights have been \rlimited, hence creating the need for new theoretical and practical explorations. For \rexample, the understanding of greenwashing behavior is still not comprehensive enough, the factors influencing the formation of greenwashing and hypocrisy in the implementation process of CSR are not thoroughly explored, the identification \revaluation system of \xe2\x80\x9ctrue green\xe2\x80\x9d vs greenwashing is not complete enough, the \rexploration of the governance mechanisms of greenwashing and hypocrisy behaviors in implementing CSR is not systematic enough, and it is difficult to obtain valid empirical data to fully identify greenwashing behavior which is somewhat unobservable and covert. All the above can restrict the development of new theoretical and empirical insights pertaining to greenwashing. Therefore, in the context of the COVID-19 epidemic, the rapid development of CSR practices in an uncertain environment calls for the simultaneous advancement of theoretical and practical research to buffer against the potential future escalation of greenwashing and decoupling behaviors in the context of CSR.\rWith this in mind, this Special Issue expects to lead the way in terms of discussions \rand research on the related issues of \xe2\x80\x9cGreenwashing in Corporate Social Responsibility\xe2\x80\x9d both at theoretical and applied levels, aiming to gather high quality interdisciplinary contributions, including conceptual and empirical papers or methodological approaches, from scholars who are actively working in this broad research area.Research Topics In recent years, greenwashing has become an emerging and hot topic in the field of corporate social responsibility area. However, the discussion of greenwashing in academic and industrial circles is still in its infancy, and there is still a lack of related influential academic achievements. The purpose of this Special Issue is to deepen the understanding of greenwashing behavior in CSR within an uncertain environment, and to find strategies to regulate and manage greenwashing and hypocrisy in implementing CSR. We call for contributions that are solid, theoretically informed, and that can offer practical insights into the greenwashing phenomenon from multiple business sub\xef\xbf\xbedisciplines. We also welcome and encourage research that capitalizes on a multi\xef\xbf\xbedisciplinary lens or perspective. Research questions and topics explored by potential contributions to this Special Issue could include, but are not limited to, the following \raspects:\r1. The nature of greenwashing behavior in CSR.\r(1) The performance dimensions of greenwashing behavior in CSR, and the differences and connections between these different dimensions. (2) Identification, measurement and assessment of greenwashing behavior in CSR. What are the criteria for identifying greenwashing behavior in CSR? How to measure and assess the greenwashing behavior in CSR based on different perspectives (such as evaluation oriented-, scoring oriented- or report oriented -views)? (3) Corporate characteristics of greenwashing behavior in CSR, under which types the firms are more prone to have greenwashing behavior in CSR, and are there certain homogeneous characteristics of these corporations? (4) CSR decoupling. What is the relationship between CSR decoupling and greenwashing behavior? What are the differences and links? (5)Corporate pseudo-social responsibility. What are the differences and links betweencorporate pseudo-social responsibility and greenwashing behavior? How to regulate the occurrence of corporate pseudo-social responsibility?\r2. The formation and evolutionary mechanism of greenwashing behavior in CSR.\rWhat are the internal and external factors that affect the formation and evolution \rof greenwashing behavior in CSR? Namely, the driving factors, occurrence, pathways \rand the evolutionary models of greenwashing behavior in CSR. \r3. The consequences of greenwashing behavior in CSR. \r(1) Individual level: The effect on employee\xe2\x80\x99s behavior etc., (2) corporate level: \rThe effect on firm reputation and performance etc., (3) society level: The effect on \rpublic attitudes and expectations etc. \r4. Governance mechanism of greenwashing behavior in CSR.\r(1) The management mechanism, supervision mechanism and governance effect of greenwashing behavior in CSR from the view of participants. (2) Stigma management of greenwashing behavior in CSR. The impacts and consequences of being stigmatized for firms involved or not involved in greenwashing behavior, and the management strategy of reducing/removing stigmatization for corporations and stakeholders.\rSubmission Instructions\rQuestions related to the Special Issue should be addressed to the guest editors Prof. dr. title: b'CIMCIA 2022'
description: b'Congreso Internacional de Mecatr\xc3\xb3nica, Control e Inteligencia Artificial'
Call For Papers: b'\nCONVOCATORIA PARA ENV\xc3\x8dO DE ART\xc3\x8dCULOS 1er. CONGRESO INTERNACIONAL DE MECATR\xc3\x93NICA, CONTROL E INTELIGENCIA ARTIFICIAL (CIMCIA).\r Los acad\xc3\xa9micos, estudiantes y universidades, generan diariamente conocimiento ingenieril de gran impacto tecnol\xc3\xb3gico y social, ideas que son capaces de cambiar los modelos de producci\xc3\xb3n, e incluso, cambiar la calidad de vida de los individuos y las sociedades. La mecatr\xc3\xb3nica, auxiliada de sistemas de control y algoritmos de inteligencia artificial, es una rama de la ingenier\xc3\xada que ha permitido el desarrollo de sistemas tecnol\xc3\xb3gicos que mejoran todos los entornos en los que se ve inmersa, tales como entornos m\xc3\xa9dicos, industriales, sociales, de entretenimiento, biol\xc3\xb3gicos,  e inclusive culturales.\r Debido a la gran importancia de desarrollo que esta rama de la ingenier\xc3\xada, y su auxiliares, pesenta, la Facultad de Estudios Superiores Cuautitl\xc3\xa1n a trav\xc3\xa9s del Grupo de Investigaci\xc3\xb3n en Sistemas Inteligentes (GISI) tiene el agrado de invitar a la comunidad acad\xc3\xa9mica, estudiantil y a todas las personas interesadas en el desarrollo de aplicaciones mecatr\xc3\xb3nicas, de control,  inteligencia artificial  y \xc3\xa1reas afines a participar en el 1er. Congreso Internacional de Mecatr\xc3\xb3nica, Control e Inteligencia Artificial (CIMCIA), a realizarse del mi\xc3\xa9rcoles 9 al viernes 11 de noviembre de 2022. \r Este congreso busca ser un foro de comunicaci\xc3\xb3n e interacci\xc3\xb3n entre la comunidad acad\xc3\xa9mica de M\xc3\xa9xico, Latinoam\xc3\xa9rica y el mundo, esperando que entre los participantes se creen v\xc3\xadnculos para el desarrollo de nuevas propuestas tecnol\xc3\xb3gicas y que a partir de ellas se generen ideas novedosas para cambiar el entorno personal y colectivo por medio de la ingenier\xc3\xada.\r Dirigido a\r Investigadores, acad\xc3\xa9micos, estudiantes de licenciatura y posgrado, as\xc3\xad como cualquier  interesado en presentar a la comunidad acad\xc3\xa9mica los resultados de sus investigaciones en el \xc3\xa1rea central,  as\xc3\xad como tambi\xc3\xa9n, prototipos y desarrollo en el \xc3\xa1rea de electr\xc3\xb3nica,  telecomunicaciones, y \xc3\xa1reas afines.\r Objetivos\r 1.\tIncentivar el desarrollo de ideas y prototipos ingenieriles que sirvan para dar soluci\xc3\xb3n a diferentes problem\xc3\xa1ticas ambientales, sociales, t\xc3\xa9cnicas o intelectuales.\r2.\tGenerar  intercambio de ideas entre los acad\xc3\xa9micos y estudiantes de las diferentes ramas de ingenier\xc3\xada que este congreso aborda.\r Bases\r Se debe de presentar un art\xc3\xadculo escrito o un cartel sobre una propuesta original, en el cual se desarrolle y describa la investigaci\xc3\xb3n realizada as\xc3\xad como los resultados obtenidos.  Como tema complementario del congreso, se realizar\xc3\xa1 el desarrollo y presentaci\xc3\xb3n de un prototipo funcional y respaldado con bases cient\xc3\xadficas, en el \xc3\xa1rea de electr\xc3\xb3nica,  telecomunicaciones, Internet de las cosas, y temas afines.\r El art\xc3\xadculo debe ser escrito en formato IEEE, que puede ser descargado de la siguiente liga:\r http://virtual.cuautitlan.unam.mx/intar/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/conference-template-a4-1.docx\r Los art\xc3\xadculos y carteles ser\xc3\xa1n evaluados por un comit\xc3\xa9 t\xc3\xa9cnico, quienes dar\xc3\xa1n la retroalimentaci\xc3\xb3n necesaria para la mejora de los trabajos enviados.\r Todos los trabajos aceptados para su presentaci\xc3\xb3n oral, as\xc3\xad como la modalidad cartel, ser\xc3\xa1n publicados en las memorias del congreso, editas por la UNAM, FES-C. \r El env\xc3\xado de trabajos, ser\xc3\xa1 por medio de la plataforma Easychair, en el momento de enviarlos, se debe seleccionar la modalidad en la que se desea participar: cartel o art\xc3\xadculo. Los art\xc3\xadculos ser\xc3\xa1n enviados por medio de la siguiente liga electr\xc3\xb3nica.\r https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=1cimcia \r Lugar\r Facultad de Estudios Superiores Cuautitl\xc3\xa1n, Carretera Cuautitl\xc3\xa1n-Teoloyucan Km. 2.5, Cuautitl\xc3\xa1n Izcalli, M\xc3\xa9x.\r Debido a las condiciones a\xc3\xban variantes por la situaci\xc3\xb3n sanitaria en la que se encuentra actualmente el pa\xc3\xads, este a\xc3\xb1o el congreso ser\xc3\xa1 en formato virtual y a distancia, a trav\xc3\xa9s de la plataforma Zoom.\r T\xc3\xb3picos\r Los t\xc3\xb3picos de inter\xc3\xa9s del congreso son los siguientes, sin estar limitados a ellos:\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tMecatr\xc3\xb3nica.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tPr\xc3\xb3tesis mecatr\xc3\xb3nicas.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tSistemas de control lineal.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tSistemas de control no lineal.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tInteligencia artificial.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRedes neuronales.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tControl difuso.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRob\xc3\xb3tica.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRob\xc3\xb3tica m\xc3\xb3vil.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tAplicaciones en rob\xc3\xb3tica.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tVeh\xc3\xadculos no tripulados.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tEdificios inteligentes.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tAutomatizaci\xc3\xb3n.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tCiudades inteligentes.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tBig Data.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tIndustria 4.0.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tInternet de las cosas.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tSistemas embebidos.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\t\xc3\x81reas afines. \r Carteles\r El cartel deber\xc3\xa1 tener un T\xc3\x8dTULO visible por lo menos a dos metros de distancia, NOMBRE completo de los autores e instituci\xc3\xb3n a la que pertenecen. Debe dise\xc3\xb1arse con las siguientes medidas: 90 cm de ancho y 120 cent\xc3\xadmetros de alto. El Cuerpo del cartel deber\xc3\xa1 contener:\r \xe2\x80\xa2\tRESUMEN,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tINTRODUCCI\xc3\x93N,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tOBJETIVOS,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tMETODOLOG\xc3\x8dA,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tRESULTADOS,\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tCONCLUSIONES\r En la modalidad virtual del congreso, los carteles ser\xc3\xa1n desplegados en una direcci\xc3\xb3n web, posteriormente definida. Una vez aceptado el cartel, se enviaran las instrucciones de presentaci\xc3\xb3n.\r Presentaci\xc3\xb3n oral\r Se considerar\xc3\xa1n para presentaci\xc3\xb3n oral, aquellos proyectos que demuestren tener alto nivel de originalidad tecnol\xc3\xb3gica y cient\xc3\xadfica. Se tendr\xc3\xa1 un tiempo de presentaci\xc3\xb3n de entre 15 y 20 minutos.\r Las presentaciones se llevaran a cabo por medio de la plataforma Zoom. Una vez aceptado el art\xc3\xadculo, se les dar\xc3\xa1n las indicaciones necesarias para su presentaci\xc3\xb3n.\r Fechas importantes\r \xe2\x80\xa2\tFecha l\xc3\xadmite para recepci\xc3\xb3n de trabajos: 10 de octubre.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tNotificaci\xc3\xb3n de aceptaci\xc3\xb3n y comentarios: 24 de octubre.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tFecha l\xc3\xadmite de recepci\xc3\xb3n de art\xc3\xadculos aceptados corregidos: 5 de noviembre.\r\xe2\x80\xa2\tCelebraci\xc3\xb3n del congreso: 9 al 11 de noviembre.\r Modo de env\xc3\xado\r Los trabajos para su revisi\xc3\xb3n por parte del comit\xc3\xa9 t\xc3\xa9cnico, deben ser enviados por medio de:\r https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=1cimcia\r Se tendr\xc3\xa1 que realizar una cuenta para poder enviar el art\xc3\xadculo.\rComentarios\r 1.\tUna vez recibida la carta de aceptaci\xc3\xb3n, \xc3\xa9l o los autores, deber\xc3\xa1n enviar una copia en PDF del cartel, las instrucciones se dar\xc3\xa1n posteriormente.\r2.\tPara poder presentar el trabajo (cartel o ponencia), al menos uno de los autores deber\xc3\xa1 presentarse a exponer el proyecto, recibir\xc3\xa1n un diploma de participaci\xc3\xb3n con el nombre del trabajo y los autores de este. El diploma ser\xc3\xa1 firmado por la direcci\xc3\xb3n de la FESC, y validado por medios electr\xc3\xb3nicos por la instituci\xc3\xb3n\r3.\tSe seleccionar\xc3\xa1n \xc3\xa9l(los) mejor(es) cartel(es) para una menci\xc3\xb3n especial.\r4.\tEl jurado ser\xc3\xa1 integrado por expertos en la materia.\r5.\tEl resultado de la evaluaci\xc3\xb3n ser\xc3\xa1 inapelable.\r6.\tTodo el proceso es completamente gratuito.\r7.\tM\xc3\xa1ximo dos art\xc3\xadculos por autor.\r8.\tPara que el art\xc3\xadculo sea incluido en las memorias debe de presentarse al menos un autor a dar la exposici\xc3\xb3n del proyecto y se deben de realizar los cambios sugeridos por los revisores del art\xc3\xadculo.\r9.\tAunque el lenguaje oficial del congreso es el espa\xc3\xb1ol, los art\xc3\xadculos y las presentaciones podr\xc3\xa1n realizarse en ingl\xc3\xa9s. \r Registro de participaci\xc3\xb3n\r Para participar en este congreso como asistente, es necesario realizar el registro por medio de la p\xc3\xa1gina electr\xc3\xb3nica (Para los asistentes se entregar\xc3\xa1 constancia firmada por los organizadores):\r https://forms.gle/auvQjoZxLXTPPuXH9 \r Informes\r Cualquier duda deber\xc3\xa1 enviarse a las direcciones de correo electr\xc3\xb3nico del comit\xc3\xa9 organizador antes mencionado, colocando en el asunto \xe2\x80\x9cCIMCIA- Dudas\xe2\x80\x9d\r Comit\xc3\xa9 organizador                cimcia@cuautitlan.unam.mx\r\n'

Workshop papers will be official publications of IEEE which will be included in IEEEXplore and also be available as printed workshop proceedings. A number of selected papers will be invited for extension and publication in a special issue of ITSE (International Journal of Interactive Technology and Smart Education) published by Emerald.\r Submission Details\r Papers must be original and not submitted to or accepted by any other conference or journal. title: b'RAI 2022'
description: b'KI Workshop on Robust AI for High-Stakes Applications'
Categories: b'artificial intelligence' b'machine learning' b'robustness' b'applications'
Call For Papers: b'\nWorkshop on Robust AI for High-Stakes Applications (RAI), collocated with KI 2022 (https://ki2022.gi.de/)\rWebsite: https://rai2022.sme.uni-bamberg.de/\r  Introduction\r========\r Robustness is widely understood as the property of some method, algorithm, or system to only decrease gradually in performance when assumptions about its input are decreasingly met. This renders robustness to be a crucial property for dependable and trustworthy applications of AI in open-world environments, in particular in high-stake applications in which human well-being is at risk. However, the usual definition of robustness raises several questions, including:\r     *What are the performance measures for evaluating the decrease in performance, i.e., which shortcomings are acceptable and which are not?\r    *How do we identify the degree to which assumptions about input characteristics are not met, in particular if assumptions are hard to specify?\r Depending on the respective application area and technique considered, various approaches have been taken to measure or benchmark performance and abnormality of input characteristics. Sometimes, we may be facing unknown requirements on input data and only experiments reveal much later that an approach is not robust (1-pixel-attacks on CNN-based object classification being one infamous example).\r There has been a lot of progress in AI over the past few years, with many successful examples in perception and reasoning, which has encouraged the integration of the resulting technologies into important and high-stakes real-world applications such as autonomous mobile systems (e.g., self-driving cars, autonomous drones, service robots) automated surgical assistants, electrical grid management systems, control of critical infrastructure, to name a few. However, for such an integration to constitute a beneficial socio-technical system, safety and reliability are key, and robustness is essential to avert potential catastrophic events due to unconsidered phenomena or situations. The aim of this workshop is to bring together researchers from basic or applied AI across all sub-fields of AI to discuss approaches and challenges for developing robust AI. In particular, we envisage a dialogue between the Machine Learning and the Symbolic AI communities for the benefit of critical real-world applications. Our aim is to foster exchange between the various AI sub-fields present at KI and to discuss future research directions.\r  Topics\r====\r Robustness refers to capability of coping with unforeseen phenomena or situations. Gearing AI towards robustness has always been an aim for open-world AI, and it becomes a pressing requirement as AI makes its way into control of high-stake applications. Robustness is addressed in many sub-fields of AI using various working definitions, and various measures. This workshop aims to bring together researchers from all sub-fields of AI working on robust methods.\r In this workshop, we invite the research community in Artificial Intelligence to submit position statements and technical works related to the theme of Robust AI for High-Stakes Applications in order to develop a joint understanding of robustness in AI and to foster the exchange on robust AI. Topics of interest include:\r     *Explainable Artificial Intelligence\r    *Benchmarking, evaluation, and regularization\r    *Regularization in Machine Learning\r    *Robust optimization\r    *Robust inference algorithms\r    *Causal model learning\r    *Neuro-symbolic integration; Logic as a referee\r    *Anomaly detection\r    *Open-world planning and decision-making\r    *AI in socio-technological systems\r The list above is by no means exhaustive, as the aim is to foster the debate around all aspects of the suggested theme.\r  Submission \r=======\rGuidelines\r------------\r We invite submissions of regular research papers, up to 12 pages in GI-LNI format, position papers, up to 6 pages, or abstracts of recently published papers, 3 pages, on the topic of robustness. Accepted papers will be published in the GI-LNI proceedings series after the KI 2022 conference. The workshop is also open to people who would like to attend without submitting a paper as discussion of the topic will play a major role. During the workshop, perspectives on proposing a special issue for the KI journal on robust AI will be discussed. Workshop submissions and camera-ready versions will be handled by EasyChair; the submission link is as follows: https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=ki2022\r Important Dates\r-------------------\r August 1, 2022: Workshop Paper Due Date\rAugust 22, 2022: Notification of Paper Acceptance\rAugust 31, 2022: Camera-ready papers due\r Note: all deadlines are Central European Time (CET), UTC +1, Paris, Brussels, Vienna.\r  Organizing Committee\r==============\r Prof. Dr. Ulrich Furbach, University of Koblenz-Landau, Germany / wizAI solutions GmbH\rDr. Alexandra Kirsch, Independent Scientist\rDr. Michael Sioutis, University of Bamberg, Germany\rProf. Dr. Diedrich Wolter, University of Bamberg, Germany\r  Contact\r=====\r All questions about submissions should be emailed to the workshop co-organizers\n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nAbout the Conference: The 3rd International Conference on Industrial IoT, Big Data and Supply Chain (IIoTBDSC 2022) \r Conference Date: September 23-25, 2022 \rVenue: Beijing, China and ONLINE\rSubmission: https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=iiotbdsc2022 due on August 15, 2022 (If you have any questions, please write to iiotbdscconference@126.com .\xef\xbc\x89\r About IIoTBDSC2022\r We live in an interconnected world that different smart devices and people are connected together. The advancement of high-tech services and reliability, efficiency, speed and accuracy of services have become crucial and popular in many aspects. The key elements include the Industrial Internet of Things, Big Data and Supply Chain.\r The Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) is a platform that allows a network of devices (sensors, smart meters, etc.) to communicate, analyze data and process information collaboratively in the service of individuals or organizations. Big Data (BD) has core values of volume, velocity, variety and veracity. Supply Chain requires the modern advancement and support from IIoT and Big Data, to make all services efficient, fast, accurate and reliable. These three can combine and work together to produce greater impacts and contributions as follows. First, the issues surrounding IIoT devices, their interconnectedness and services they may offer, including efficient, effective and secure analysis of the data IIoT produces. Often machine learning and other advanced techniques, models and tools, and issues of security and trust are related. The maturity of IoT technologies can grow and become part of our everyday lives. Second, BD can be jointly used with machine learning, AI, statistical and other advanced techniques, models and methods, which can create values for people and organizations adopting it. Forecasting, deep analysis and analytics can help identify weaknesses and make improvements based on different analysis. Third, suppliers can know the updates on their stocks and demands. Manufacturers and transport companies know the workloads, destination and resource distributions. Finally, customers can know the real-time updates of the delivery of their goods. Investors can better decisions on their goods, resources, sales and management. Supply chain can reach a greater sustainable ecosystem with the help of IIoT and Big Data.\r This conference brings the experts, practitioners, scientists and decision-makers from academia and industry together. Our aim is to foster a strong, lively and well-connected international research community. We welcome innovative ideas, concepts, services, techniques, research outputs and business practices.\r Conference History\r IIoTBDSC2021(The 2nd session of IIoTBDSC2021) was successfully held on October 15-17, 2021 online, and all of the accepted papers had been published in conference proceedings by International Conference Proceeding Series, and submitted to ISI Proceedings (ISTP/CPCI), EI Compendex, DBLP, SCOPUS, Google Scholar for indexing.\rMore information on publication of IIoTBDSC2021, please hit the link: https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/conference-proceedings-of-SPIE/12128.toc\r  Important Dates\r Final Submission Due: August 8, 2022\rNotification of Acceptance: August 31, 2022\rFinal Version with Copy Right: September 10, 2022\rConference Date: September 23-25, 2022\r Journals\r Some of the best papers of IIoTBDSC2022 will have the chances to be recommended to SCI / EI journals for publishing, In such case, the papers must be significantly changed after improvement and expanding - usually, at least 30% changes are requested.  \r Collaborating journals\rWe will work with a number of high quality and indexed journals (SCI, SSCI, EI, ESCI, ABS, Scopus) including: \r 1. Call For Papers: b"\nSpecial Issue Editor\rProf. Dr. Victor Chang \r Guest Editor\rDepartment of Operations and Information Management, Aston Business School, Aston University, Birmingham B4 7ET, UK\r Interests: fintech; data science; Internet of Things; cloud/fog/edge computing and security with risk\rSpecial Issues, Collections and Topics in MDPI journals\r Special Issue Information\r Dear Colleagues,\r We live in an interconnected world where different smart devices and people are connected together. The key elements include the Industrial Internet of Things, big data, and supply chains.\r The Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) is a platform that allows a network of devices (sensors, smart meters, etc.) to communicate, analyze data, and process information collaboratively in the service of individuals or organizations. Big data (BD) have the core values of volume, velocity, variety, and veracity. Supply chains require modern advancement and support from the IIoT and big data to make all services efficient, fast, accurate, and reliable. These three can combine and work together to produce greater impacts and contributions, such as in the issues surrounding IIoT devices, their interconnectedness, and the services they may offer, including efficient, effective, and secure analysis of the data IIoT produces. Second, BD can be jointly used with machine learning, AI, and statistical and other advanced techniques, models, and methods, which can create value for the people and organizations adopting it. Forecasting, deep analysis, and analytics can help to identify weaknesses and make improvements based on different analyses. Third, suppliers can receive real-time updates on their stocks and demands, manufacturers and transport companies on the workloads, destination, and resource distributions, and customers on the delivery of their goods. Investors can make better decisions regarding their goods, resources, sales, and management, and supply chains can achieve a greater sustainable ecosystem with the help of IIoT and Big Data.\r This Special Issue brings experts, practitioners, scientists, and decision makers from academia and industry together. Our aim is to foster a strong, lively, and well-connected international research community. We welcome innovative ideas, concepts, services, techniques, research outputs, and industrial applications. We will select the top authors from IIoTBDSC 2022 http://iiotbdsc.com/2022/, but we also welcome any authors with regular paper submissions.\r Prof. Dr. Victor Chang\rGuest Editor\r Manuscript Submission Information\r Manuscripts should be submitted online at www.mdpi.com by registering and logging in to this website. Once you are registered, click here to go to the submission form. Manuscripts can be submitted until the deadline. All submissions that pass pre-check are peer-reviewed. For planned papers, a title and short abstract (about 100 words) can be sent to the Editorial Office for announcement on this website.\r Submitted manuscripts should not have been published previously, nor be under consideration for publication elsewhere (except conference proceedings papers). All manuscripts are thoroughly refereed through a single-blind peer-review process. A guide for authors and other relevant information for submission of manuscripts is available on the Instructions for Authors page. Electronics is an international peer-reviewed open access semimonthly journal published by MDPI.\r Please visit the Instructions for Authors page before submitting a manuscript. The Article Processing Charge (APC) for publication in this open access journal is 2000 CHF (Swiss Francs). Submitted papers should be well formatted and use good English. Authors may use MDPI's English editing service prior to publication or during author revisions.\r \n"

title: b'ISPD 2023'
description: b'International Symposium on Physical Design 2023'
Call For Papers: b'\nCALL FOR PAPERS \xe2\x80\x93 ISPD 2023\r ACM International Symposium on Physical Design\rwith a tribute to Professor Malgorzata Marek-Sadowska\rMarch 26-29, 2023, Virtual    http://www.ispd.cc/ \rSponsored by ACM SIGDA with technical co-sponsorship from IEEE CEDA\r The International Symposium on Physical Design (ISPD) provides a\rpremier forum to exchange ideas and promote innovative research in all\raspects of physical design ranging from traditional topics for ASIC\rand FPGA designs to emerging technologies that impact physical design\rof integrated circuits (ICs). In 2023, ISPD will be online with\rvirtual participation, with both live video and recorded sessions. The\r32nd symposium will highlight key new directions and leading-edge\rtheoretical and experimental contributions to the field.\r Physical design topics of interest include but are not limited to: \rFloorplanning and interconnect planning\rPartitioning, placement, and routing\rClock and power networks\rPost layout and post-silicon optimization\rDesign for manufacturability and yield\rPhysical synthesis\rInteractions with system and logic level design\rTiming and power estimation, modeling, and optimization\rCircuit analysis and optimization in a physical design context\rData management, multi-threaded/distributed algorithms\rHot topics such as machine learning and hardware security\r3D ICs, quantum circuits, and other emerging technologies\r IMPORTANT DATES \t\r Title and abstract submission deadline            September 30, 2022\t\t\t\rFull manuscript submission deadline               October 7, 2022\t\t\t\t\rAcceptance notification                           November 11, 2022\t\t\t\t\rCamera-ready paper and speaker registration due\t  January 30, 2023\rSymposium                                         March 26-29, 2023\r SUBMISSION OF PAPERS\r All papers must be submitted electronically via\rhttps://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=ispd2023. Details will be\rposted on the ISPD website, http://www.ispd.cc. Authors must submit\rfull-length, original papers, with a maximum of 8 pages using the ACM\rtemplate, https://www.acm.org/publications/proceedings-template, in\rPDF format. Failure to comply with the page length limit, format, or\rthe requirements below will result in the paper being rejected.\r Previously published papers or papers currently submitted for\rpublication elsewhere will not be considered. If related papers have\rbeen published or submitted elsewhere, clearly state the differences\rin the current submission. All submitted papers will be under blind\rreview. They must not include the names or affiliations of the authors\rin the paper, abstract, or in the embedded PDF data. References to the\rauthors\xe2\x80\x99 works must be in the third person. Papers with open-source\rsoftware (e.g., on GitHub) are highly encouraged, but please do not\rinclude a direct link to the non-anonymized software in your\rsubmission, instead indicate the open-source contribution in the text.\r The symposium proceedings will be published in the ACM Digital Library.\rISPD recognizes excellent contributions with a Best Paper Award,\rselected from among the submitted papers. There is a US$1,000 award for\rthe best paper, and a smaller award for best paper candidates.\r One speaker per accepted paper must register for ISPD 2023, provide\rslides and videos of their presentation, and attend live discussions\rin the online session. The slides will be published on the ISPD website.\rThe authors will retain the copyright for the slides and videos, which\rwill be posted on a private YouTube channel for ISPD 2023.\r By submitting your article to an ACM Publication, you acknowledge that\ryou and your co-authors are subject to all ACM Publications Policies\r(https://www.acm.org/publications/policies),\rincluding Research Involving Human Participants and Subjects (https://\rwww.acm.org/publications/policies/\rresearch-involving-human-participants-and-subjects).\rViolations will be investigated by ACM and may result in a full\rretraction of a paper, in addition to other potential penalties.\r For an accepted paper, authors must obtain an ORCID ID to publish it.\r(https://orcid.org/register) ACM is rolling this out as a requirement\rin 2022 \xe2\x80\x93 please see the\rfrequently asked questions for more details.\r(https://authors.acm.org/author-resources/orcid-faqs) This is to\rimprove author discoverability, ensure proper attribution and help\rcommunity efforts around name normalization.\r   \n'

title: b'EAI Urb-IoT 2022'
description: b'7th EAI International Conference on IoT in Urban Space'
Call For Papers: b'\nScope\r Urb-IoT is a European Alliance for Innovation (EAI) International Conference providing an open forum for presentations in the field of Internet of Things (IoT). The conference aims to provide opportunities for highly innovative research and industrial practices to significantly impact the advancement of the IoT technologies. This year, the Urban-IoT conference will focus on the intelligent sensing for real-time data analytics with high emphasis on Intelligent Sensing, All Technologies and Real-time data Analytics for IoT. EAI Urb-IoT 2022 will be held as an on-site conference with an option to present remotely. The conference will be held in Toronto, Ontario, Canada from October 31st to November 3rd, 2022.\r ***\r General Chair\rKhalid Elgazzar, Ontario Tech University\r Technical Program Commmittee Chairs\rPetros Spachos, University of Guelph\rAhmed Refaey Hussein, University of Guelph\r ***\r Publication\r All registered papers will be submitted for publishing by Springer and made available through SpringerLink Digital Library.\r Proceedings will be submitted for inclusion in leading indexing services, such as Web of Science, Compendex, Scopus, DBLP, EU Digital Library, IO-Port, MatchSciNet, Inspec and Zentralblatt MATH.\r Authors of selected best accepted and presented papers will be invited to submit an extended version to:\r- Springer Journal on Wireless Networks (WINET) (IF: 2.659)\r All accepted authors are eligible to submit an extended version in a fast track of:\r- EAI Endorsed Transactions on Industrial Networks and Intelligent Systems indexed in Scopus\r- EAI Endorsed Transactions on Internet of Things\r Additional publication opportunities:\r- EAI/Springer Innovations in Communications and Computing Book Series\r(titles in this series are indexed in Ei Compendex, Web of Science & Scopus)\r ***\r Topics\r The topics of nterest include:\r - Edge computing for urban sensing and IoT\r- Machine learning for urban IoT\r- Network processing and data analytics for urban IoT systems\r- Artificial Intelligence and AI Technologies for IoT\r- IoT Architectures Interoperable and collaborative IoT\r- Edge AI/edge computing\r- Web of Things and Technologies for large scale IoT\r- IoT Communication Technologies, Energy Efficiency and Sustainability in IoT\r- Performance evaluation of IoT systems\r- Industrial Internet of Things\r- Digital Twin for Industrial Settings\r- Novel Applications of IoT\r- Ubiquitous and pervasive computing\r- Intelligent Sensing Technologies\r- Real-time Aata Analytics for IoT\r- Security and Privacy in IoT\r- Biometrics Pattern Recognition\r- Computer Vision Applied to IoT\r- Applications for e-Health and Wellbeing\r- Connected and Autonomous vehicles\r- Time Series Analysis for IoT\r  ***\r EAI Urb-IoT 2022 will be held as an on-site conference and if needed, Accepted Authors who are unable to attend the event in person will be given an option to present remotely.\r ***\r This event is organized by EAI (www.eai.eu).\r EAI \xe2\x80\x93 European Alliance for Innovation is a non-profit organization and a professional community established in cooperation with the European Commission to empower global research and innovation, and to promote cooperation between European and International ICT communities.\n\t'

description: b'NFDI4Ing Conference 2022: Unifying the Understanding of RDM in Engineering Science'
Categories: b'research data management' b'data management' b'fair data' b'engineering'
Call For Papers: b'\nTo those interested in research data management in egineering, \r For Wednesday and Thursday, October 26 and 27, 2022, we cordially invite you to our annual conference. \r Overview:\rWhen?        \tOctober 26 and 27, 2022, 9:00 to 17:00 (CET) \rWhere?          Online \rWho?            Everyone interested in research data management in engineering, may it be researchers, teachers or industry representatives\rWhat?           Unify the understanding of RDM in engineering theory and practice through discussions, presentations of use cases as well as demonstrations\r The conference will take place online and is free of charge for all participants. Detailed information about the event can be found and will continuously be updated at the link below:\rhttps://nfdi4ing.de/conference.\r The aim of the conference is to advance and unify international (research) data management and to foster exchange. We will discuss open issues and future challenges on topics such as terminologies, metadata, ontologies, repositories and many more. Likewise, opportunities for networking and exchange with the research community will be provided.\r Everyone is invited to contribute. Accepted contributions will be eligible to hand in a full paper, that is planned to be published in a special issue of ing.grid, the first international journal on research data management in engineering sciences. Additionally, we will grant a best contribution award.\r Therefore, it is our pleasure to invite you to contribute your perspective on RDM in engineering to the conference. If interested, an abstract (500 - 1000 words) for a presentation, tutorial, demonstration, workshop or other contribution can be submitted via the conference website until 13th of August 2022:\rhttps://nfdi4ing.de/conference_abstract_submission/\r The time slot your successful contribution receives is free for you to fill. Possible contributions include, but are not limited to, tutorials, tech demos, presentations or workshops. \rThe reserved time slots are set to 30 minutes. You may fill the complete slot with your contribution or finish early to leave room for discussion.\r We look forward to seeing you at our virtual conference - exciting presentations await us!\r Kind regards,\rThe NFDI4Ing Conference Organising Committee\n\t'

Call For Papers: b'\nThe International Symposium on Design and Diagnostics of Electronic Circuits and Systems (DDECS) provides a forum for exchanging ideas, discussing research results, and presenting practical applications in the areas of design, test, and diagnosis of nanoelectronic digital, analog, and mixed-signal circuits and systems. The 26th edition of the DDECS Symposium will be held in Tallinn, the capital of the Estonia, which is is one of the best-preserved medieval cities in Europe.\r The areas of interest include (but are not limited to) the following topics:\r Topic 1. Analog, Mixed Signal, RF and Sensors\rAnalog and mixed-signal circuits design and test\rWireless circuits and systems\rHigh-frequency circuits\rSensor technologies\rRF design and test\rAnalog neuromorphic circuits\r Topic 2. Test, Verification and Dependability\rCircuits and systems test\rReliability and robustness of DNNs\rFault-tolerance\rSelf-health awareness and fault management\rTest infrastructures\rDiagnosis and debug\rFormal and simulation-based verification\rFunctional safety\rReliability\rML-based test and dependability solutions\r Topic 4. Secure HW and Embedded Systems\rCryptographic implementations\rAttacks against implementations\rSide-channel analysis\rTrusted computing platforms\rIP protection and reverse engineering\rHardware trojans\r Topic 5. Emerging Technologies and New Computing Paradigms\rBrain-inspired computing\rPolymorphic and ambipolar circuits\rReversible logic\rQuantum computing\rQuantum dot cellular automata\rStochastic computing\rIn-memory computing\rMemristor technology\rEmerging memory devices\rSilicon photonics\rMicrofluidics and biochips\rDNA computing\r Publication and submission:\rDDECS 2023 seeks original, unpublished contributions of the following types:\rRegular Papers presenting novel and complete research work (6 pages)\rStudent Papers from students eager to discuss their on-going research (4 pages)\r DDECS review process is single-blind, i.e. the author information is not hidden.\rAccepted papers will be submitted for inclusion into IEEE Xplore.\r Further information\rGeneral Chair\r  Maksim Jenihhin, TalTech, EE maksim.jenihhin@taltech.ee\r Program Chairs\r  Nele Mentens, KU Leuven, BE nele.mentens@kuleuven.be\r  Jaan Raik, TalTech, EE jaan.raik@taltech.ee\r  \n'

Call For Papers: b'\nCall for Papers: International Studies (Winter 2022, 22/2)\r Dear colleagues, \r International Studies now cordially invites articles for its Winter 2022 issue. In addition to papers within the broader thematic scope of the journal, the Winter 2022 issue includes a special thematic interest in the topic \xe2\x80\x9cInternational Relations after 2022\xe2\x80\x9d.\r International Studies is a double-blind peer-reviewed scholarly journal published by Libertas International University (Zagreb, Croatia). The journal welcomes submissions within its thematic scope that includes international relations, foreign policy, international economics, and related fields such as the social sciences, humanities, political science, economics, history, philosophy, etc. The journal approaches international relations in a broader sense and encourages an interdisciplinary approach. \rArticles are accepted and published in either English or Croatian. The journal is published biannually in Platinum Open Access and does not charge any article submission or processing fees. International Studies is indexed in over 20 scholarly databases and services, including CEEOL, DOAJ, EBSCOhost, ERIH PLUS, ProQuest, and RePEc. Book reviews are also welcome.\r The world has gone through a series of fundamental changes in the last six years, with various crucial aspects of international relations challenged or reversed. In 2016, the ever-widening and ever-deepening nature of the EU was challenged with the Brexit vote victorious in the UK. Globalization and the hegemonic position of the US at its center was challenged in several ways: with the electoral victory of Donald Trump on a protectionist ticket in 2016, with various challenges to the US relationship with key international organizations including the UN, NATO and the WTO; with a partial reversal of trade liberalization including a tariff war with China with its apex in 2018/19. The COVID-19 crisis of 2020 redefined the relationship between private and public sectors and included levels of interventionism unseen in several generations. It also caused enormous supply-side shocks, and indirectly helped cause severe inflation episodes in the developed world, the results of which are not yet fully visible. In early 2022, the Russia-Ukraine conflict expanded to levels not seen in Europe since the post-Yugoslav wars in the early 1990s (and before that, since World War 2). The economic fall-out has increased the danger of inflation in the developed world and threatens to cause famine in the developing world. The political fall-out is still uncertain but will alter the position of a number of states in the international order. These developments are intertwined and open a series of urgent questions.\r Questions within the special thematic interest \xe2\x80\x9cInternational Relations after 2022\xe2\x80\x9d include, but are not limited to:\r - The economic globalization agenda: Damage to the idea of free trade?\r- Hegemonic shift: Changes to positions of the US and China\r- Russia after 2022: An empire reborn?\r- Quo Vadis, EU?: The capacities to survive, expand, deepen the integration and/or formulate a foreign policy\r- Future evolution of international organizations: the futures of NATO, UN, WHO, WTO\r- Russia, China, Turkey, EU and the US in the Balkans - interplay of the changing agendas in a contested space\r The article submission deadline is 20 September 2022. Articles should be sent to the journal\xe2\x80\x99s Editor-in-Chief, dr. Vladimir Filipovi\xc4\x87, at vfilipovic@libertas.hr. Please consult the Instructions for authors before submitting your contributions.\r For more information, please consult our website or write to vfilipovic@libertas.hr.  \r\n'
